{"label": 0, "text": "Right Concentration.Visakha Now what is concentration, what qualities are its themes, what qualities are its requisites, and what is its development?VisakhaSister Dhammadinna Singleness of mind is concentration; the four frames of reference are its themes; the four right exertions are its requisites; and any cultivation, development, & pursuit of these qualities is its development.Sister Dhammadinna"}
{"label": 0, "text": "These are the four developments of concentration."}
{"label": 0, "text": "What four?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "There is the development of concentration that, when developed & pursued, leads to a pleasant abiding in the here & now."}
{"label": 0, "text": "There is the development of concentration that."}
{"label": 0, "text": "leads to the attainment of knowledge & vision."}
{"label": 0, "text": "There is the development of concentration that."}
{"label": 0, "text": "leads to mindfulness & alertness."}
{"label": 0, "text": "There is the development of concentration that, when developed & pursued, leads to the ending of the effluents.And what is the development of concentration that, when developed & pursued, leads to a pleasant abiding in the here & now?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "There is the case where a monk  quite withdrawn from sensuality, withdrawn from unskillful qualities  enters & remains in the first jhana rapture & pleasure born from withdrawal, accompanied by directed thought & evaluation."}
{"label": 0, "text": "With the stilling of directed thoughts & evaluations, he enters & remains in the second jhana rapture & pleasure born of composure, unification of awareness free from directed thought & evaluation  internal assurance."}
{"label": 0, "text": "With the fading of rapture, he remains equanimous, mindful, & alert, and senses pleasure with the body."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He enters & remains in the third jhana, of which the Noble Ones declare, 'Equanimous & mindful, he has a pleasant abiding.' With the abandoning of pleasure & pain  as with the earlier disappearance of elation & distress  he enters & remains in the fourth jhana purity of equanimity & mindfulness, neither pleasure nor pain."}
{"label": 0, "text": "This is the development of concentration that."}
{"label": 0, "text": "leads to a pleasant abiding in the here & now.And what is the development of concentration that."}
{"label": 0, "text": "leads to the attainment of knowledge & vision?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "There is the case where a monk has the perception of light, the perception of daytime (at any hour of the day) well-fixed & well in hand."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Day (for him) is the same as night, night is the same as day."}
{"label": 0, "text": "By means of an awareness open & unhampered, he develops a brightened mind."}
{"label": 0, "text": "This is the development of concentration that."}
{"label": 0, "text": "leads to the attainment of knowledge & vision.And what is the development of concentration that."}
{"label": 0, "text": "leads to mindfulness & alertness?"}
