{"label": 0, "text": "Now what, monks, is the five-factored noble right concentration?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "There is the case where a monk  quite withdrawn from sensuality, withdrawn from unskillful (mental) qualities  enters & remains in the first jhana rapture & pleasure born from withdrawal, accompanied by directed thought & evaluation."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He permeates & pervades, suffuses & fills this very body with the rapture & pleasure born from withdrawal."}
{"label": 0, "text": "There is nothing of his entire body unpervaded by rapture & pleasure born from withdrawal.Just as if a skilled bathman or bathman's apprentice would pour bath powder into a brass basin and knead it together, sprinkling it again & again with water, so that his ball of bath powder  saturated, moisture-laden, permeated within & without  would nevertheless not drip; even so, monks, the monk permeates."}
{"label": 0, "text": "this very body with the rapture & pleasure born of withdrawal."}
{"label": 0, "text": "There is nothing of his entire body unpervaded by rapture & pleasure born from withdrawal."}
{"label": 0, "text": "This is the first development of the five-factored noble right concentration.Furthermore, with the stilling of directed thoughts & evaluations, he enters & remains in the second jhana rapture & pleasure born of composure, one-pointedness of awareness free from directed thought & evaluation  internal assurance."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He permeates & pervades, suffuses & fills this very body with the rapture & pleasure born of composure."}
{"label": 0, "text": "There is nothing of his entire body unpervaded by rapture & pleasure born of composure.Just like a lake with spring-water welling up from within, having no inflow from east, west, north or south, and with the skies periodically supplying abundant showers, so that the cool fount of water welling up from within the lake would permeate & pervade, suffuse & fill it with cool waters, there being no part of the lake unpervaded by the cool waters; even so monks, the monk permeates."}
{"label": 0, "text": "this very body with the rapture & pleasure born of composure."}
{"label": 0, "text": "There is nothing of his entire body unpervaded by rapture & pleasure born of composure."}
{"label": 0, "text": "This is the second development of the five-factored noble right concentration.And furthermore, with the fading of rapture, he remains equanimous, mindful, & alert, and senses pleasure with the body."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He enters & remains in the third jhana, of which the Noble Ones declare, 'Equanimous & mindful, he has a pleasant abiding.' He permeates & pervades, suffuses & fills this very body with the pleasure divested of rapture, so that there is nothing of his entire body unpervaded with pleasure divested of rapture.Just as in a blue-, white-, or red-lotus pond, there may be some of the blue, white, or red lotuses which, born & growing in the water, stay immersed in the water and flourish without standing up out of the water, so that they are permeated & pervaded, suffused & filled with cool water from their roots to their tips, and nothing of those blue, white, or red lotuses would be unpervaded with cool water; even so, monks, the monk permeates."}
{"label": 0, "text": "this very body with the pleasure divested of rapture."}
{"label": 0, "text": "There is nothing of his entire body unpervaded with pleasure divested of rapture."}
{"label": 0, "text": "This is the third development of the five-factored noble right concentration.And furthermore, with the abandoning of pleasure & stress  as with the earlier disappearance of elation & distress  he enters & remains in the fourth jhana purity of equanimity & mindfulness, neither-pleasure-nor-pain."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He sits, permeating the body with a pure, bright awareness, so that there is nothing of his entire body unpervaded by pure, bright awareness.Just as if a man were sitting covered from head to foot with a white cloth so that there would be no part of his body to which the white cloth did not extend; even so, monks, the monk sits, permeating his body with a pure, bright awareness."}
{"label": 0, "text": "There is nothing of his entire body unpervaded by pure, bright awareness."}
{"label": 0, "text": "This is the fourth development of the five-factored noble right concentration.And furthermore, the monk has his theme of reflection well in hand, well attended to, well-pondered, well-penetrated by means of discernment.Just as if one person were to reflect on another, or a standing person were to reflect on a sitting person, or a sitting person were to reflect on a person lying down; even so, monks, the monk has his theme of reflection well in hand, well attended to, well-pondered, well-penetrated by means of discernment."}
{"label": 0, "text": "This is the fifth development of the five-factored noble right concentration.When a monk has developed & pursued the five-factored noble right concentration in this way, then whichever of the six higher knowledges he turns his mind to know & realize, he can witness them for himself whenever there is an opening.Suppose that there were a water jar, set on a stand, brimful of water so that a crow could drink from it."}
{"label": 0, "text": "If a strong man were to tip it in any way at all, would water spill out?Yes, lord.In the same way, when a monk has developed & pursued the five-factored noble right concentration in this way, then whichever of the six higher knowledges he turns his mind to know & realize, he can witness them for himself whenever there is an opening.Suppose there were a rectangular water tank  set on level round, bounded by dykes  brimful of water so that a crow could drink from it."}
{"label": 0, "text": "If a strong man were to loosen the dykes anywhere at all, would water spill out?Yes, lord.Suppose there were a chariot on level ground at four crossroads, harnessed to thoroughbreds, waiting with whips lying ready, so that a skilled driver, a trainer of tamable horses, might mount and  taking the reins with his left hand and the whip with his right  drive out & back, to whatever place and by whichever road he liked; in the same way, when a monk has developed & pursued the five-factored noble right concentration in this way, then whichever of the six higher knowledges he turns his mind to know & realize, he can witness them for himself whenever there is an opening."}
{"label": 0, "text": "There's no jhana for one with\tno discernment, no discernment for one with\tno jhana."}
{"label": 0, "text": "But one with both jhana & discernment is on the verge of Unbinding."}
{"label": 0, "text": " Dhp"}
{"label": 0, "text": "Concentration & Discernment.Suppose that an archer or archer's apprentice were to practice on a straw man or mound of clay, so that after a while he would become able to shoot long distances, to fire accurate shots in rapid succession, & to pierce great masses."}
{"label": 0, "text": "In the same way, there is the case where a monk."}
{"label": 0, "text": "enters & remains in the first jhana rapture & pleasure born of withdrawal, accompanied by directed thought & evaluation."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He regards whatever phenomena there that are connected with form, feeling, perception, fabrications, & consciousness as inconstant, stressful, a disease, a cancer, an arrow, painful, an affliction, alien, a dissolution, an emptiness, not-self."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He turns his mind away from those phenomena, and having done so, inclines his mind to the quality of deathlessness 'This is peace, this is exquisite  the resolution of all fabrications, the relinquishment of all mental acquisitions, the passing away of craving, dispassion, cessation, Unbinding.'Having attained this point, he reaches the ending of the mental fermentations."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Or, if not, then  through passion & delight for this very quality [the discernment inclining to deathlessness] and from the total wasting away of the first five of the Fetters [self-identity views, grasping at precepts & practices, uncertainty, sensual passion, and resistance]  he is due to be reborn [in the Pure Abodes], there to be totally unbound, never again to return from that world."}
{"label": 0, "text": "(Similarly with the remaining levels of jhana.)"}
{"label": 0, "text": "Discernment & Release.With his mind thus concentrated, purified, & bright, the monk directs it to the knowledge of the ending of the mental fermentations."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Just as if there were a pool of water in a mountain glen  clear, limpid, & unsullied  where a man with good eyesight standing on the bank could see shells, gravel, & pebbles, and also shoals of fish swimming about & resting, and it would occur to him, 'This pool of water is clear, limpid, & unsullied."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Here are these shells, gravel, & pebbles, and also these shoals of fish swimming about & resting.' In the same way, the monk discerns, as it has come to be, that 'This is stress."}
{"label": 0, "text": "This is the origination of stress."}
{"label": 0, "text": "This is the cessation of stress."}
{"label": 0, "text": "This is the way leading to the cessation of stress."}
{"label": 0, "text": "These are mental fermentations."}
{"label": 0, "text": "This is the origination of fermentations."}
{"label": 0, "text": "This is the cessation of fermentations."}
{"label": 0, "text": "This is the way leading to the cessation of fermentations.' His heart, thus knowing, thus seeing, is released from the fermentations of sensuality, becoming, & ignorance."}
{"label": 0, "text": "With release, there is the knowledge, 'Released.' He discerns that 'Birth is ended, the holy life fulfilled, the task done."}
{"label": 0, "text": "There is nothing further for this world.' This, too, is a reward of the contemplative life, visible here & now, more excellent than the previous ones and more sublime."}
{"label": 0, "text": "And as for another visible fruit of the contemplative life, higher & more sublime than this, there is none."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Washing my feet, I noticed the water."}
{"label": 0, "text": "And in watching it flow from high to low, my heart was composed like a fine thoroughbred steed."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Then taking a lamp, I entered the hut, checked the bedding, sat down on the bed."}
{"label": 0, "text": "And taking a pin, I pulled out the wick Like the flame's unbinding was the liberation of awareness."}
{"label": 0, "text": " Thig ."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The Tao that can be trodden is not the enduring and unchanging Tao."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The name that can be named is not the enduring and unchanging name."}
{"label": 0, "text": "(Conceived of as) having no name, it is the Originator of heaven and earth; (conceived of as) having a name, it is the Mother of all things."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Always without desire we must be found, If its deep mystery we would sound; But if desire always within us be, Its outer fringe is all that we shall see."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Under these two aspects, it is really the same; but as development takes place, it receives the different names."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Together we call them the Mystery."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Where the Mystery is the deepest is the gate of all that is subtle and wonderful."}
{"label": 0, "text": "All in the world know the beauty of the beautiful, and in doing this they have (the idea of) what ugliness is; they all know the skill of the skilful, and in doing this they have (the idea of) what the want of skill is."}
{"label": 0, "text": "So it is that existence and non-existence give birth the one to (the idea of) the other; that difficulty and ease produce the one (the idea of) the other; that length and shortness fashion out the one the figure of the other; that (the ideas of) height and lowness arise from the contrast of the one with the other; that the musical notes and tones become harmonious through the relation of one with another; and that being before and behind give the idea of one following another."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore the sage manages affairs without doing anything, and conveys his instructions without the use of speech."}
{"label": 0, "text": "All things spring up, and there is not one which declines to show itself; they grow, and there is no claim made for their ownership; they go through their processes, and there is no expectation (of a reward for the results)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The work is accomplished, and there is no resting in it (as an achievement)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The work is done, but how no one can see; 'Tis this that makes the power not cease to be."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Not to value and employ men of superior ability is the way to keep the people from rivalry among themselves; not to prize articles which are difficult to procure is the way to keep them from becoming thieves; not to show them what is likely to excite their desires is the way to keep their minds from disorder."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore the sage, in the exercise of his government, empties their minds, fills their bellies, weakens their wills, and strengthens their bones."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He constantly (tries to) keep them without knowledge and without desire, and where there are those who have knowledge, to keep them from presuming to act (on it)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "When there is this abstinence from action, good order is universal."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The Tao is (like) the emptiness of a vessel; and in our employment of it we must be on our guard against all fulness."}
{"label": 0, "text": "How deep and unfathomable it is, as if it were the Honoured Ancestor of all things!"}
{"label": 0, "text": "We should blunt our sharp points, and unravel the complications of things; we should attemper our brightness, and bring ourselves into agreement with the obscurity of others."}
{"label": 0, "text": "How pure and still the Tao is, as if it would ever so continue!"}
{"label": 0, "text": "I do not know whose son it is."}
{"label": 0, "text": "It might appear to have been before God."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Heaven and earth do not act from (the impulse of) any wish to be benevolent; they deal with all things as the dogs of grass are dealt with."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The sages do not act from (any wish to be) benevolent; they deal with the people as the dogs of grass are dealt with."}
{"label": 0, "text": "May not the space between heaven and earth be compared to a bellows?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "'Tis emptied, yet it loses not its power; 'Tis moved again, and sends forth air the more."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Much speech to swift exhaustion lead we see; Your inner being guard, and keep it free."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The valley spirit dies not, aye the same; The female mystery thus do we name."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Its gate, from which at first they issued forth, Is called the root from which grew heaven and earth."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Long and unbroken does its power remain, Used gently, and without the touch of pain."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Heaven is long-enduring and earth continues long."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The reason why heaven and earth are able to endure and continue thus long is because they do not live of, or for, themselves."}
{"label": 0, "text": "This is how they are able to continue and endure."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore the sage puts his own person last, and yet it is found in the foremost place; he treats his person as if it were foreign to him, and yet that person is preserved."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Is it not because he has no personal and private ends, that therefore such ends are realised?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "The highest excellence is like (that of) water."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The excellence of water appears in its benefiting all things, and in its occupying, without striving (to the contrary), the low place which all men dislike."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Hence (its way) is near to (that of) the Tao."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The excellence of a residence is in (the suitability of) the place; that of the mind is in abysmal stillness; that of associations is in their being with the virtuous; that of government is in its securing good order; that of (the conduct of) affairs is in its ability; and that of (the initiation of) any movement is in its timeliness."}
{"label": 0, "text": "And when (one with the highest excellence) does not wrangle (about his low position), no one finds fault with him."}
{"label": 0, "text": "It is better to leave a vessel unfilled, than to attempt to carry it when it is full."}
{"label": 0, "text": "If you keep feeling a point that has been sharpened, the point cannot long preserve its sharpness."}
{"label": 0, "text": "When gold and jade fill the hall, their possessor cannot keep them safe."}
{"label": 0, "text": "When wealth and honours lead to arrogancy, this brings its evil on itself."}
{"label": 0, "text": "When the work is done, and one's name is becoming distinguished, to withdraw into obscurity is the way of Heaven."}
{"label": 0, "text": "When the intelligent and animal souls are held together in one embrace, they can be kept from separating."}
{"label": 0, "text": "When one gives undivided attention to the (vital) breath, and brings it to the utmost degree of pliancy, he can become as a (tender) babe."}
{"label": 0, "text": "When he has cleansed away the most mysterious sights (of his imagination), he can become without a flaw."}
{"label": 0, "text": "In loving the people and ruling the state, cannot he proceed without any (purpose of) action?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "In the opening and shutting of his gates of heaven, cannot he do so as a female bird?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "While his intelligence reaches in every direction, cannot he (appear to) be without knowledge?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "(The Tao) produces (all things) and nourishes them; it produces them and does not claim them as its own; it does all, and yet does not boast of it; it presides over all, and yet does not control them."}
{"label": 0, "text": "This is what is called 'The mysterious Quality' (of the Tao)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The thirty spokes unite in the one nave; but it is on the empty space (for the axle), that the use of the wheel depends."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Clay is fashioned into vessels; but it is on their empty hollowness, that their use depends."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The door and windows are cut out (from the walls) to form an apartment; but it is on the empty space (within), that its use depends."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore, what has a (positive) existence serves for profitable adaptation, and what has not that for (actual) usefulness."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Colour's five hues from th' eyes their sight will take; Music's five notes the ears as deaf can make; The flavours five deprive the mouth of taste; The chariot course, and the wild hunting waste Make mad the mind; and objects rare and strange, Sought for, men's conduct will to evil change."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore the sage seeks to satisfy (the craving of) the belly, and not the (insatiable longing of the) eyes."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He puts from him the latter, and prefers to seek the former."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Favour and disgrace would seem equally to be feared; honour and great calamity, to be regarded as personal conditions (of the same kind)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "What is meant by speaking thus of favour and disgrace?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "Disgrace is being in a low position (after the enjoyment of favour)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The getting that (favour) leads to the apprehension (of losing it), and the losing it leads to the fear of (still greater calamity)--this is what is meant by saying that favour and disgrace would seem equally to be feared."}
{"label": 0, "text": "And what is meant by saying that honour and great calamity are to be (similarly) regarded as personal conditions?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "What makes me liable to great calamity is my having the body (which I call myself); if I had not the body, what great calamity could come to me?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore he who would administer the kingdom, honouring it as he honours his own person, may be employed to govern it, and he who would administer it with the love which he bears to his own person may be entrusted with it."}
{"label": 0, "text": "We look at it, and we do not see it, and we name it 'the Equable.' We listen to it, and we do not hear it, and we name it 'the Inaudible.' We try to grasp it, and do not get hold of it, and we name it 'the Subtle.' With these three qualities, it cannot be made the subject of description; and hence we blend them together and obtain The One."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Its upper part is not bright, and its lower part is not obscure."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Ceaseless in its action, it yet cannot be named, and then it again returns and becomes nothing."}
{"label": 0, "text": "This is called the Form of the Formless, and the Semblance of the Invisible; this is called the Fleeting and Indeterminable."}
{"label": 0, "text": "We meet it and do not see its Front; we follow it, and do not see its Back."}
{"label": 0, "text": "When we can lay hold of the Tao of old to direct the things of the present day, and are able to know it as it was of old in the beginning, this is called (unwinding) the clue of Tao."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The skilful masters (of the Tao) in old times, with a subtle and exquisite penetration, comprehended its mysteries, and were deep (also) so as to elude men's knowledge."}
{"label": 0, "text": "As they were thus beyond men's knowledge, I will make an effort to describe of what sort they appeared to be."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Shrinking looked they like those who wade through a stream in winter; irresolute like those who are afraid of all around them; grave like a guest (in awe of his host); evanescent like ice that is melting away; unpretentious like wood that has not been fashioned into anything; vacant like a valley, and dull like muddy water."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Who can (make) the muddy water (clear)?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "Let it be still, and it will gradually become clear."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Who can secure the condition of rest?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "Let movement go on, and the condition of rest will gradually arise."}
{"label": 0, "text": "They who preserve this method of the Tao do not wish to be full (of themselves)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "It is through their not being full of themselves that they can afford to seem worn and not appear new and complete."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The (state of) vacancy should be brought to the utmost degree, and that of stillness guarded with unwearying vigour."}
{"label": 0, "text": "All things alike go through their processes of activity, and (then) we see them return (to their original state)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "When things (in the vegetable world) have displayed their luxuriant growth, we see each of them return to its root."}
{"label": 0, "text": "This returning to their root is what we call the state of stillness; and that stillness may be called a reporting that they have fulfilled their appointed end."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The report of that fulfilment is the regular, unchanging rule."}
{"label": 0, "text": "To know that unchanging rule is to be intelligent; not to know it leads to wild movements and evil issues."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The knowledge of that unchanging rule produces a (grand) capacity and forbearance, and that capacity and forbearance lead to a community (of feeling with all things)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "From this community of feeling comes a kingliness of character; and he who is king-like goes on to be heaven-like."}
{"label": 0, "text": "In that likeness to heaven he possesses the Tao."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Possessed of the Tao, he endures long; and to the end of his bodily life, is exempt from all danger of decay."}
{"label": 0, "text": "In the highest antiquity, (the people) did not know that there were (their rulers)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "In the next age they loved them and praised them."}
{"label": 0, "text": "In the next they feared them; in the next they despised them."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Thus it was that when faith (in the Tao) was deficient (in the rulers) a want of faith in them ensued (in the people)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "How irresolute did those (earliest rulers) appear, showing (by their reticence) the importance which they set upon their words!"}
{"label": 0, "text": "Their work was done and their undertakings were successful, while the people all said, 'We are as we are, of ourselves!'"}
{"label": 0, "text": "When the Great Tao (Way or Method) ceased to be observed, benevolence and righteousness came into vogue."}
{"label": 0, "text": "(Then) appeared wisdom and shrewdness, and there ensued great hypocrisy."}
{"label": 0, "text": "When harmony no longer prevailed throughout the six kinships, filial sons found their manifestation; when the states and clans fell into disorder, loyal ministers appeared."}
{"label": 0, "text": "If we could renounce our sageness and discard our wisdom, it would be better for the people a hundredfold."}
{"label": 0, "text": "If we could renounce our benevolence and discard our righteousness, the people would again become filial and kindly."}
{"label": 0, "text": "If we could renounce our artful contrivances and discard our (scheming for) gain, there would be no thieves nor robbers."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Those three methods (of government) Thought olden ways in elegance did fail And made these names their want of worth to veil; But simple views, and courses plain and true Would selfish ends and many lusts eschew."}
{"label": 0, "text": "When we renounce learning we have no troubles."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The (ready) 'yes,' and (flattering) 'yea;'-- Small is the difference they display."}
{"label": 0, "text": "But mark their issues, good and ill;-- What space the gulf between shall fill?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "What all men fear is indeed to be feared; but how wide and without end is the range of questions (asking to be discussed)!"}
{"label": 0, "text": "The multitude of men look satisfied and pleased; as if enjoying a full banquet, as if mounted on a tower in spring."}
{"label": 0, "text": "I alone seem listless and still, my desires having as yet given no indication of their presence."}
{"label": 0, "text": "I am like an infant which has not yet smiled."}
{"label": 0, "text": "I look dejected and forlorn, as if I had no home to go to."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The multitude of men all have enough and to spare."}
{"label": 0, "text": "I alone seem to have lost everything."}
{"label": 0, "text": "My mind is that of a stupid man; I am in a state of chaos."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Ordinary men look bright and intelligent, while I alone seem to be benighted."}
{"label": 0, "text": "They look full of discrimination, while I alone am dull and confused."}
{"label": 0, "text": "I seem to be carried about as on the sea, drifting as if I had nowhere to rest."}
{"label": 0, "text": "All men have their spheres of action, while I alone seem dull and incapable, like a rude borderer."}
{"label": 0, "text": "(Thus) I alone am different from other men, but I value the nursing-mother (the Tao)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The grandest forms of active force From Tao come, their only source."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Who can of Tao the nature tell?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "Our sight it flies, our touch as well."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Eluding sight, eluding touch, The forms of things all in it crouch; Eluding touch, eluding sight, There are their semblances, all right."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Profound it is, dark and obscure; Things' essences all there endure."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Those essences the truth enfold Of what, when seen, shall then be told."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Now it is so; 'twas so of old."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Its name--what passes not away; So, in their beautiful array, Things form and never know decay."}
{"label": 0, "text": "How know I that it is so with all the beauties of existing things?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "By this (nature of the Tao)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The partial becomes complete; the crooked, straight; the empty, full; the worn out, new."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He whose (desires) are few gets them; he whose (desires) are many goes astray."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore the sage holds in his embrace the one thing (of humility), and manifests it to all the world."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He is free from self- display, and therefore he shines; from self-assertion, and therefore he is distinguished; from self-boasting, and therefore his merit is acknowledged; from self-complacency, and therefore he acquires superiority."}
{"label": 0, "text": "It is because he is thus free from striving that therefore no one in the world is able to strive with him."}
{"label": 0, "text": "That saying of the ancients that 'the partial becomes complete' was not vainly spoken--all real completion is comprehended under it."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Abstaining from speech marks him who is obeying the spontaneity of his nature."}
{"label": 0, "text": "A violent wind does not last for a whole morning; a sudden rain does not last for the whole day."}
{"label": 0, "text": "To whom is it that these (two) things are owing?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "To Heaven and Earth."}
{"label": 0, "text": "If Heaven and Earth cannot make such (spasmodic) actings last long, how much less can man!"}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore when one is making the Tao his business, those who are also pursuing it, agree with him in it, and those who are making the manifestation of its course their object agree with him in that; while even those who are failing in both these things agree with him where they fail."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Hence, those with whom he agrees as to the Tao have the happiness of attaining to it; those with whom he agrees as to its manifestation have the happiness of attaining to it; and those with whom he agrees in their failure have also the happiness of attaining (to the Tao)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "(But) when there is not faith sufficient (on his part), a want of faith (in him) ensues (on the part of the others)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He who stands on his tiptoes does not stand firm; he who stretches his legs does not walk (easily)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "(So), he who displays himself does not shine; he who asserts his own views is not distinguished; he who vaunts himself does not find his merit acknowledged; he who is self- conceited has no superiority allowed to him."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Such conditions, viewed from the standpoint of the Tao, are like remnants of food, or a tumour on the body, which all dislike."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Hence those who pursue (the course) of the Tao do not adopt and allow them."}
{"label": 0, "text": "There was something undefined and complete, coming into existence before Heaven and Earth."}
{"label": 0, "text": "How still it was and formless, standing alone, and undergoing no change, reaching everywhere and in no danger (of being exhausted)!"}
{"label": 0, "text": "It may be regarded as the Mother of all things."}
{"label": 0, "text": "I do not know its name, and I give it the designation of the Tao (the Way or Course)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Making an effort (further) to give it a name I call it The Great."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Great, it passes on (in constant flow)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Passing on, it becomes remote."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Having become remote, it returns."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore the Tao is great; Heaven is great; Earth is great; and the (sage) king is also great."}
{"label": 0, "text": "In the universe there are four that are great, and the (sage) king is one of them."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Man takes his law from the Earth; the Earth takes its law from Heaven; Heaven takes its law from the Tao."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The law of the Tao is its being what it is."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Gravity is the root of lightness; stillness, the ruler of movement."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore a wise prince, marching the whole day, does not go far from his baggage waggons."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Although he may have brilliant prospects to look at, he quietly remains (in his proper place), indifferent to them."}
{"label": 0, "text": "How should the lord of a myriad chariots carry himself lightly before the kingdom?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "If he do act lightly, he has lost his root (of gravity); if he proceed to active movement, he will lose his throne."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The skilful traveller leaves no traces of his wheels or footsteps; the skilful speaker says nothing that can be found fault with or blamed; the skilful reckoner uses no tallies; the skilful closer needs no bolts or bars, while to open what he has shut will be impossible; the skilful binder uses no strings or knots, while to unloose what he has bound will be impossible."}
{"label": 0, "text": "In the same way the sage is always skilful at saving men, and so he does not cast away any man; he is always skilful at saving things, and so he does not cast away anything."}
{"label": 0, "text": "This is called 'Hiding the light of his procedure.' Therefore the man of skill is a master (to be looked up to) by him who has not the skill; and he who has not the skill is the helper of (the reputation of) him who has the skill."}
{"label": 0, "text": "If the one did not honour his master, and the other did not rejoice in his helper, an (observer), though intelligent, might greatly err about them."}
{"label": 0, "text": "This is called 'The utmost degree of mystery.'"}
{"label": 0, "text": "Who knows his manhood's strength, Yet still his female feebleness maintains; As to one channel flow the many drains, All come to him, yea, all beneath the sky."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Thus he the constant excellence retains; The simple child again, free from all stains."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Who knows how white attracts, Yet always keeps himself within black's shade, The pattern of humility displayed, Displayed in view of all beneath the sky; He in the unchanging excellence arrayed, Endless return to man's first state has made."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Who knows how glory shines, Yet loves disgrace, nor e'er for it is pale; Behold his presence in a spacious vale, To which men come from all beneath the sky."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The unchanging excellence completes its tale; The simple infant man in him we hail."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The unwrought material, when divided and distributed, forms vessels."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The sage, when employed, becomes the Head of all the Officers (of government); and in his greatest regulations he employs no violent measures."}
{"label": 0, "text": "If any one should wish to get the kingdom for himself, and to effect this by what he does, I see that he will not succeed."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The kingdom is a spirit-like thing, and cannot be got by active doing."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He who would so win it destroys it; he who would hold it in his grasp loses it."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The course and nature of things is such that What was in front is now behind; What warmed anon we freezing find."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Strength is of weakness oft the spoil; The store in ruins mocks our toil."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Hence the sage puts away excessive effort, extravagance, and easy indulgence."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He who would assist a lord of men in harmony with the Tao will not assert his mastery in the kingdom by force of arms."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Such a course is sure to meet with its proper return."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Wherever a host is stationed, briars and thorns spring up."}
{"label": 0, "text": "In the sequence of great armies there are sure to be bad years."}
{"label": 0, "text": "A skilful (commander) strikes a decisive blow, and stops."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He does not dare (by continuing his operations) to assert and complete his mastery."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He will strike the blow, but will be on his guard against being vain or boastful or arrogant in consequence of it."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He strikes it as a matter of necessity; he strikes it, but not from a wish for mastery."}
{"label": 0, "text": "When things have attained their strong maturity they become old."}
{"label": 0, "text": "This may be said to be not in accordance with the Tao and what is not in accordance with it soon comes to an end."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Now arms, however beautiful, are instruments of evil omen, hateful, it may be said, to all creatures."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore they who have the Tao do not like to employ them."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The superior man ordinarily considers the left hand the most honourable place, but in time of war the right hand."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Those sharp weapons are instruments of evil omen, and not the instruments of the superior man;--he uses them only on the compulsion of necessity."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Calm and repose are what he prizes; victory (by force of arms) is to him undesirable."}
{"label": 0, "text": "To consider this desirable would be to delight in the slaughter of men; and he who delights in the slaughter of men cannot get his will in the kingdom."}
{"label": 0, "text": "On occasions of festivity to be on the left hand is the prized position; on occasions of mourning, the right hand."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The second in command of the army has his place on the left; the general commanding in chief has his on the right;--his place, that is, is assigned to him as in the rites of mourning."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He who has killed multitudes of men should weep for them with the bitterest grief; and the victor in battle has his place (rightly) according to those rites."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The Tao, considered as unchanging, has no name."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Though in its primordial simplicity it may be small, the whole world dares not deal with (one embodying) it as a minister."}
{"label": 0, "text": "If a feudal prince or the king could guard and hold it, all would spontaneously submit themselves to him."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Heaven and Earth (under its guidance) unite together and send down the sweet dew, which, without the directions of men, reaches equally everywhere as of its own accord."}
{"label": 0, "text": "As soon as it proceeds to action, it has a name."}
{"label": 0, "text": "When it once has that name, (men) can know to rest in it."}
{"label": 0, "text": "When they know to rest in it, they can be free from all risk of failure and error."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The relation of the Tao to all the world is like that of the great rivers and seas to the streams from the valleys."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He who knows other men is discerning; he who knows himself is intelligent."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He who overcomes others is strong; he who overcomes himself is mighty."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He who is satisfied with his lot is rich; he who goes on acting with energy has a (firm) will."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He who does not fail in the requirements of his position, continues long; he who dies and yet does not perish, has longevity."}
{"label": 0, "text": "All-pervading is the Great Tao!"}
{"label": 0, "text": "It may be found on the left hand and on the right."}
{"label": 0, "text": "All things depend on it for their production, which it gives to them, not one refusing obedience to it."}
{"label": 0, "text": "When its work is accomplished, it does not claim the name of having done it."}
{"label": 0, "text": "It clothes all things as with a garment, and makes no assumption of being their lord;--it may be named in the smallest things."}
{"label": 0, "text": "All things return (to their root and disappear), and do not know that it is it which presides over their doing so;--it may be named in the greatest things."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Hence the sage is able (in the same way) to accomplish his great achievements."}
{"label": 0, "text": "It is through his not making himself great that he can accomplish them."}
{"label": 0, "text": "To him who holds in his hands the Great Image (of the invisible Tao), the whole world repairs."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Men resort to him, and receive no hurt, but (find) rest, peace, and the feeling of ease."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Music and dainties will make the passing guest stop (for a time)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "But though the Tao as it comes from the mouth, seems insipid and has no flavour, though it seems not worth being looked at or listened to, the use of it is inexhaustible."}
{"label": 0, "text": "When one is about to take an inspiration, he is sure to make a (previous) expiration; when he is going to weaken another, he will first strengthen him; when he is going to overthrow another, he will first have raised him up; when he is going to despoil another, he will first have made gifts to him--this is called 'Hiding the light (of his procedure).' The soft overcomes the hard; and the weak the strong."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Fishes should not be taken from the deep; instruments for the profit of a state should not be shown to the people."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The Tao in its regular course does nothing (for the sake of doing it), and so there is nothing which it does not do."}
{"label": 0, "text": "If princes and kings were able to maintain it, all things would of themselves be transformed by them."}
{"label": 0, "text": "If this transformation became to me an object of desire, I would express the desire by the nameless simplicity."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Simplicity without a name Is free from all external aim."}
{"label": 0, "text": "With no desire, at rest and still, All things go right as of their will."}
{"label": 0, "text": "(Those who) possessed in highest degree the attributes (of the Tao) did not (seek) to show them, and therefore they possessed them (in fullest measure)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "(Those who) possessed in a lower degree those attributes (sought how) not to lose them, and therefore they did not possess them (in fullest measure)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "(Those who) possessed in the highest degree those attributes did nothing (with a purpose), and had no need to do anything."}
{"label": 0, "text": "(Those who) possessed them in a lower degree were (always) doing, and had need to be so doing."}
{"label": 0, "text": "(Those who) possessed the highest benevolence were (always seeking) to carry it out, and had no need to be doing so."}
{"label": 0, "text": "(Those who) possessed the highest righteousness were (always seeking) to carry it out, and had need to be so doing."}
{"label": 0, "text": "(Those who) possessed the highest (sense of) propriety were (always seeking) to show it, and when men did not respond to it, they bared the arm and marched up to them."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Thus it was that when the Tao was lost, its attributes appeared; when its attributes were lost, benevolence appeared; when benevolence was lost, righteousness appeared; and when righteousness was lost, the proprieties appeared."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Now propriety is the attenuated form of leal-heartedness and good faith, and is also the commencement of disorder; swift apprehension is (only) a flower of the Tao, and is the beginning of stupidity."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Thus it is that the Great man abides by what is solid, and eschews what is flimsy; dwells with the fruit and not with the flower."}
{"label": 0, "text": "It is thus that he puts away the one and makes choice of the other."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The things which from of old have got the One (the Tao) are-- Heaven which by it is bright and pure; Earth rendered thereby firm and sure; Spirits with powers by it supplied; Valleys kept full throughout their void All creatures which through it do live Princes and kings who from it get The model which to all they give."}
{"label": 0, "text": "All these are the results of the One (Tao)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "If heaven were not thus pure, it soon would rend; If earth were not thus sure, 'twould break and bend; Without these powers, the spirits soon would fail; If not so filled, the drought would parch each vale; Without that life, creatures would pass away; Princes and kings, without that moral sway, However grand and high, would all decay."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Thus it is that dignity finds its (firm) root in its (previous) meanness, and what is lofty finds its stability in the lowness (from which it rises)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Hence princes and kings call themselves 'Orphans,' 'Men of small virtue,' and as 'Carriages without a nave.' Is not this an acknowledgment that in their considering themselves mean they see the foundation of their dignity?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "So it is that in the enumeration of the different parts of a carriage we do not come on what makes it answer the ends of a carriage."}
{"label": 0, "text": "They do not wish to show themselves elegant-looking as jade, but (prefer) to be coarse-looking as an (ordinary) stone."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The movement of the Tao By contraries proceeds; And weakness marks the course Of Tao's mighty deeds."}
{"label": 0, "text": "All things under heaven sprang from It as existing (and named); that existence sprang from It as non-existent (and not named)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Scholars of the highest class, when they hear about the Tao, earnestly carry it into practice."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Scholars of the middle class, when they have heard about it, seem now to keep it and now to lose it."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Scholars of the lowest class, when they have heard about it, laugh greatly at it."}
{"label": 0, "text": "If it were not (thus) laughed at, it would not be fit to be the Tao."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore the sentence-makers have thus expressed themselves-- 'The Tao, when brightest seen, seems light to lack; Who progress in it makes, seems drawing back; Its even way is like a rugged track."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Its highest virtue from the vale doth rise; Its greatest beauty seems to offend the eyes; And he has most whose lot the least supplies."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Its firmest virtue seems but poor and low; Its solid truth seems change to undergo; Its largest square doth yet no corner show A vessel great, it is the slowest made; Loud is its sound, but never word it said; A semblance great, the shadow of a shade.' The Tao is hidden, and has no name; but it is the Tao which is skilful at imparting (to all things what they need) and making them complete."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The Tao produced One; One produced Two; Two produced Three; Three produced All things."}
{"label": 0, "text": "All things leave behind them the Obscurity (out of which they have come), and go forward to embrace the Brightness (into which they have emerged), while they are harmonised by the Breath of Vacancy."}
{"label": 0, "text": "What men dislike is to be orphans, to have little virtue, to be as carriages without naves; and yet these are the designations which kings and princes use for themselves."}
{"label": 0, "text": "So it is that some things are increased by being diminished, and others are diminished by being increased."}
{"label": 0, "text": "What other men (thus) teach, I also teach."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The violent and strong do not die their natural death."}
{"label": 0, "text": "I will make this the basis of my teaching."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The softest thing in the world dashes against and overcomes the hardest; that which has no (substantial) existence enters where there is no crevice."}
{"label": 0, "text": "I know hereby what advantage belongs to doing nothing (with a purpose)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "There are few in the world who attain to the teaching without words, and the advantage arising from non-action."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Or fame or life, Which do you hold more dear?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "Or life or wealth, To which would you adhere?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "Keep life and lose those other things; Keep them and lose your life--which brings Sorrow and pain more near?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "Thus we may see, Who cleaves to fame Rejects what is more great; Who loves large stores Gives up the richer state."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Who is content Needs fear no shame."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Who knows to stop Incurs no blame."}
{"label": 0, "text": "From danger free Long live shall he."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Who thinks his great achievements poor Shall find his vigour long endure."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Of greatest fulness, deemed a void, Exhaustion ne'er shall stem the tide."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Do thou what's straight still crooked deem; Thy greatest art still stupid seem, And eloquence a stammering scream."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Constant action overcomes cold; being still overcomes heat."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Purity and stillness give the correct law to all under heaven."}
{"label": 0, "text": "When the Tao prevails in the world, they send back their swift horses to (draw) the dung-carts."}
{"label": 0, "text": "When the Tao is disregarded in the world, the war-horses breed in the border lands."}
{"label": 0, "text": "There is no guilt greater than to sanction ambition; no calamity greater than to be discontented with one's lot; no fault greater than the wish to be getting."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore the sufficiency of contentment is an enduring and unchanging sufficiency."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Without going outside his door, one understands (all that takes place) under the sky; without looking out from his window, one sees the Tao of Heaven."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The farther that one goes out (from himself), the less he knows."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore the sages got their knowledge without travelling; gave their (right) names to things without seeing them; and accomplished their ends without any purpose of doing so."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He who devotes himself to learning (seeks) from day to day to increase (his knowledge); he who devotes himself to the Tao (seeks) from day to day to diminish (his doing)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He diminishes it and again diminishes it, till he arrives at doing nothing (on purpose)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Having arrived at this point of non-action, there is nothing which he does not do."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He who gets as his own all under heaven does so by giving himself no trouble (with that end)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "If one take trouble (with that end), he is not equal to getting as his own all under heaven."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The sage has no invariable mind of his own; he makes the mind of the people his mind."}
{"label": 0, "text": "To those who are good (to me), I am good; and to those who are not good (to me), I am also good;--and thus (all) get to be good."}
{"label": 0, "text": "To those who are sincere (with me), I am sincere; and to those who are not sincere (with me), I am also sincere;--and thus (all) get to be sincere."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The sage has in the world an appearance of indecision, and keeps his mind in a state of indifference to all."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The people all keep their eyes and ears directed to him, and he deals with them all as his children."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Men come forth and live; they enter (again) and die."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Of every ten three are ministers of life (to themselves); and three are ministers of death."}
{"label": 0, "text": "There are also three in every ten whose aim is to live, but whose movements tend to the land (or place) of death."}
{"label": 0, "text": "And for what reason?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "Because of their excessive endeavours to perpetuate life."}
{"label": 0, "text": "But I have heard that he who is skilful in managing the life entrusted to him for a time travels on the land without having to shun rhinoceros or tiger, and enters a host without having to avoid buff coat or sharp weapon."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The rhinoceros finds no place in him into which to thrust its horn, nor the tiger a place in which to fix its claws, nor the weapon a place to admit its point."}
{"label": 0, "text": "And for what reason?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "Because there is in him no place of death."}
{"label": 0, "text": "All things are produced by the Tao, and nourished by its outflowing operation."}
{"label": 0, "text": "They receive their forms according to the nature of each, and are completed according to the circumstances of their condition."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore all things without exception honour the Tao, and exalt its outflowing operation."}
{"label": 0, "text": "This honouring of the Tao and exalting of its operation is not the result of any ordination, but always a spontaneous tribute."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Thus it is that the Tao produces (all things), nourishes them, brings them to their full growth, nurses them, completes them, matures them, maintains them, and overspreads them."}
{"label": 0, "text": "It produces them and makes no claim to the possession of them; it carries them through their processes and does not vaunt its ability in doing so; it brings them to maturity and exercises no control over them;--this is called its mysterious operation."}
{"label": 0, "text": "(The Tao) which originated all under the sky is to be considered as the mother of them all."}
{"label": 0, "text": "When the mother is found, we know what her children should be."}
{"label": 0, "text": "When one knows that he is his mother's child, and proceeds to guard (the qualities of) the mother that belong to him, to the end of his life he will be free from all peril."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Let him keep his mouth closed, and shut up the portals (of his nostrils), and all his life he will be exempt from laborious exertion."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Let him keep his mouth open, and (spend his breath) in the promotion of his affairs, and all his life there will be no safety for him."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The perception of what is small is (the secret of clear- sightedness; the guarding of what is soft and tender is (the secret of) strength."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Who uses well his light, Reverting to its (source so) bright, Will from his body ward all blight, And hides the unchanging from men's sight."}
{"label": 0, "text": "If I were suddenly to become known, and (put into a position to) conduct (a government) according to the Great Tao, what I should be most afraid of would be a boastful display."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The great Tao (or way) is very level and easy; but people love the by-ways."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Their court(-yards and buildings) shall be well kept, but their fields shall be ill-cultivated, and their granaries very empty."}
{"label": 0, "text": "They shall wear elegant and ornamented robes, carry a sharp sword at their girdle, pamper themselves in eating and drinking, and have a superabundance of property and wealth;--such (princes) may be called robbers and boasters."}
{"label": 0, "text": "This is contrary to the Tao surely!"}
{"label": 0, "text": "What (Tao's) skilful planter plants Can never be uptorn; What his skilful arms enfold, From him can ne'er be borne."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Sons shall bring in lengthening line, Sacrifices to his shrine."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Tao when nursed within one's self, His vigour will make true; And where the family it rules What riches will accrue!"}
{"label": 0, "text": "The neighbourhood where it prevails In thriving will abound; And when 'tis seen throughout the state, Good fortune will be found."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Employ it the kingdom o'er, And men thrive all around."}
{"label": 0, "text": "In this way the effect will be seen in the person, by the observation of different cases; in the family; in the neighbourhood; in the state; and in the kingdom."}
{"label": 0, "text": "How do I know that this effect is sure to hold thus all under the sky?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "By this (method of observation)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He who has in himself abundantly the attributes (of the Tao) is like an infant."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Poisonous insects will not sting him; fierce beasts will not seize him; birds of prey will not strike him."}
{"label": 0, "text": "(The infant's) bones are weak and its sinews soft, but yet its grasp is firm."}
{"label": 0, "text": "It knows not yet the union of male and female, and yet its virile member may be excited;--showing the perfection of its physical essence."}
{"label": 0, "text": "All day long it will cry without its throat becoming hoarse;--showing the harmony (in its constitution)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "To him by whom this harmony is known, (The secret of) the unchanging (Tao) is shown, And in the knowledge wisdom finds its throne."}
{"label": 0, "text": "All life-increasing arts to evil turn; Where the mind makes the vital breath to burn, (False) is the strength, (and o'er it we should mourn.) When things have become strong, they (then) become old, which may be said to be contrary to the Tao."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Whatever is contrary to the Tao soon ends."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He who knows (the Tao) does not (care to) speak (about it); he who is (ever ready to) speak about it does not know it."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He (who knows it) will keep his mouth shut and close the portals (of his nostrils)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He will blunt his sharp points and unravel the complications of things; he will attemper his brightness, and bring himself into agreement with the obscurity (of others)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "This is called 'the Mysterious Agreement.' (Such an one) cannot be treated familiarly or distantly; he is beyond all consideration of profit or injury; of nobility or meanness--he is the noblest man under heaven."}
{"label": 0, "text": "A state may be ruled by (measures of) correction; weapons of war may be used with crafty dexterity; (but) the kingdom is made one's own (only) by freedom from action and purpose."}
{"label": 0, "text": "How do I know that it is so?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "By these facts--In the kingdom the multiplication of prohibitive enactments increases the poverty of the people; the more implements to add to their profit that the people have, the greater disorder is there in the state and clan; the more acts of crafty dexterity that men possess, the more do strange contrivances appear; the more display there is of legislation, the more thieves and robbers there are."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore a sage has said, 'I will do nothing (of purpose), and the people will be transformed of themselves; I will be fond of keeping still, and the people will of themselves become correct."}
{"label": 0, "text": "I will take no trouble about it, and the people will of themselves become rich; I will manifest no ambition, and the people will of themselves attain to the primitive simplicity.'"}
{"label": 0, "text": "The government that seems the most unwise, Oft goodness to the people best supplies; That which is meddling, touching everything, Will work but ill, and disappointment bring."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Misery!--happiness is to be found by its side!"}
{"label": 0, "text": "Happiness!--misery lurks beneath it!"}
{"label": 0, "text": "Who knows what either will come to in the end?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "Shall we then dispense with correction?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "The (method of) correction shall by a turn become distortion, and the good in it shall by a turn become evil."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The delusion of the people (on this point) has indeed subsisted for a long time."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore the sage is (like) a square which cuts no one (with its angles); (like) a corner which injures no one (with its sharpness)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He is straightforward, but allows himself no license; he is bright, but does not dazzle."}
{"label": 0, "text": "For regulating the human (in our constitution) and rendering the (proper) service to the heavenly, there is nothing like moderation."}
{"label": 0, "text": "It is only by this moderation that there is effected an early return (to man's normal state)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "That early return is what I call the repeated accumulation of the attributes (of the Tao)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "With that repeated accumulation of those attributes, there comes the subjugation (of every obstacle to such return)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Of this subjugation we know not what shall be the limit; and when one knows not what the limit shall be, he may be the ruler of a state."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He who possesses the mother of the state may continue long."}
{"label": 0, "text": "His case is like that (of the plant) of which we say that its roots are deep and its flower stalks firm--this is the way to secure that its enduring life shall long be seen."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Governing a great state is like cooking small fish."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Let the kingdom be governed according to the Tao, and the manes of the departed will not manifest their spiritual energy."}
{"label": 0, "text": "It is not that those manes have not that spiritual energy, but it will not be employed to hurt men."}
{"label": 0, "text": "It is not that it could not hurt men, but neither does the ruling sage hurt them."}
{"label": 0, "text": "When these two do not injuriously affect each other, their good influences converge in the virtue (of the Tao)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "What makes a great state is its being (like) a low-lying, down- flowing (stream);--it becomes the centre to which tend (all the small states) under heaven."}
{"label": 0, "text": "(To illustrate from) the case of all females--the female always overcomes the male by her stillness."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Stillness may be considered (a sort of) abasement."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Thus it is that a great state, by condescending to small states, gains them for itself; and that small states, by abasing themselves to a great state, win it over to them."}
{"label": 0, "text": "In the one case the abasement leads to gaining adherents, in the other case to procuring favour."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The great state only wishes to unite men together and nourish them; a small state only wishes to be received by, and to serve, the other."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Each gets what it desires, but the great state must learn to abase itself."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Tao has of all things the most honoured place."}
{"label": 0, "text": "No treasures give good men so rich a grace; Bad men it guards, and doth their ill efface."}
{"label": 0, "text": "(Its) admirable words can purchase honour; (its) admirable deeds can raise their performer above others."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Even men who are not good are not abandoned by it."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore when the sovereign occupies his place as the Son of Heaven, and he has appointed his three ducal ministers, though (a prince) were to send in a round symbol-of-rank large enough to fill both the hands, and that as the precursor of the team of horses (in the court-yard), such an offering would not be equal to (a lesson of) this Tao, which one might present on his knees."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Why was it that the ancients prized this Tao so much?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "Was it not because it could be got by seeking for it, and the guilty could escape (from the stain of their guilt) by it?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "This is the reason why all under heaven consider it the most valuable thing."}
{"label": 0, "text": "(It is the way of the Tao) to act without (thinking of) acting; to conduct affairs without (feeling the) trouble of them; to taste without discerning any flavour; to consider what is small as great, and a few as many; and to recompense injury with kindness."}
{"label": 0, "text": "(The master of it) anticipates things that are difficult while they are easy, and does things that would become great while they are small."}
{"label": 0, "text": "All difficult things in the world are sure to arise from a previous state in which they were easy, and all great things from one in which they were small."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore the sage, while he never does what is great, is able on that account to accomplish the greatest things."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He who lightly promises is sure to keep but little faith; he who is continually thinking things easy is sure to find them difficult."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore the sage sees difficulty even in what seems easy, and so never has any difficulties."}
{"label": 0, "text": "That which is at rest is easily kept hold of; before a thing has given indications of its presence, it is easy to take measures against it; that which is brittle is easily broken; that which is very small is easily dispersed."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Action should be taken before a thing has made its appearance; order should be secured before disorder has begun."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The tree which fills the arms grew from the tiniest sprout; the tower of nine storeys rose from a (small) heap of earth; the journey of a thousand li commenced with a single step."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He who acts (with an ulterior purpose) does harm; he who takes hold of a thing (in the same way) loses his hold."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The sage does not act (so), and therefore does no harm; he does not lay hold (so), and therefore does not lose his bold."}
{"label": 0, "text": "(But) people in their conduct of affairs are constantly ruining them when they are on the eve of success."}
{"label": 0, "text": "If they were careful at the end, as (they should be) at the beginning, they would not so ruin them."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore the sage desires what (other men) do not desire, and does not prize things difficult to get; he learns what (other men) do not learn, and turns back to what the multitude of men have passed by."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Thus he helps the natural development of all things, and does not dare to act (with an ulterior purpose of his own)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The ancients who showed their skill in practising the Tao did so, not to enlighten the people, but rather to make them simple and ignorant."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The difficulty in governing the people arises from their having much knowledge."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He who (tries to) govern a state by his wisdom is a scourge to it; while he who does not (try to) do so is a blessing."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He who knows these two things finds in them also his model and rule."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Ability to know this model and rule constitutes what we call the mysterious excellence (of a governor)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Deep and far-reaching is such mysterious excellence, showing indeed its possessor as opposite to others, but leading them to a great conformity to him."}
{"label": 0, "text": "That whereby the rivers and seas are able to receive the homage and tribute of all the valley streams, is their skill in being lower than they;--it is thus that they are the kings of them all."}
{"label": 0, "text": "So it is that the sage (ruler), wishing to be above men, puts himself by his words below them, and, wishing to be before them, places his person behind them."}
{"label": 0, "text": "In this way though he has his place above them, men do not feel his weight, nor though he has his place before them, do they feel it an injury to them."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore all in the world delight to exalt him and do not weary of him."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Because he does not strive, no one finds it possible to strive with him."}
{"label": 0, "text": "All the world says that, while my Tao is great, it yet appears to be inferior (to other systems of teaching)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Now it is just its greatness that makes it seem to be inferior."}
{"label": 0, "text": "If it were like any other (system), for long would its smallness have been known!"}
{"label": 0, "text": "But I have three precious things which I prize and hold fast."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The first is gentleness; the second is economy; and the third is shrinking from taking precedence of others."}
{"label": 0, "text": "With that gentleness I can be bold; with that economy I can be liberal; shrinking from taking precedence of others, I can become a vessel of the highest honour."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Now-a-days they give up gentleness and are all for being bold; economy, and are all for being liberal; the hindmost place, and seek only to be foremost;--(of all which the end is) death."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Gentleness is sure to be victorious even in battle, and firmly to maintain its ground."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Heaven will save its possessor, by his (very) gentleness protecting him."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He who in (Tao's) wars has skill Assumes no martial port; He who fights with most good will To rage makes no resort."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He who vanquishes yet still Keeps from his foes apart; He whose hests men most fulfil Yet humbly plies his art."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Thus we say, 'He ne'er contends, And therein is his might.' Thus we say, 'Men's wills he bends, That they with him unite.' Thus we say, 'Like Heaven's his ends, No sage of old more bright.'"}
{"label": 0, "text": "A master of the art of war has said, 'I do not dare to be the host (to commence the war); I prefer to be the guest (to act on the defensive)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "I do not dare to advance an inch; I prefer to retire a foot.' This is called marshalling the ranks where there are no ranks; baring the arms (to fight) where there are no arms to bare; grasping the weapon where there is no weapon to grasp; advancing against the enemy where there is no enemy."}
{"label": 0, "text": "There is no calamity greater than lightly engaging in war."}
{"label": 0, "text": "To do that is near losing (the gentleness) which is so precious."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Thus it is that when opposing weapons are (actually) crossed, he who deplores (the situation) conquers."}
{"label": 0, "text": "My words are very easy to know, and very easy to practise; but there is no one in the world who is able to know and able to practise them."}
{"label": 0, "text": "There is an originating and all-comprehending (principle) in my words, and an authoritative law for the things (which I enforce)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "It is because they do not know these, that men do not know me."}
{"label": 0, "text": "They who know me are few, and I am on that account (the more) to be prized."}
{"label": 0, "text": "It is thus that the sage wears (a poor garb of) hair cloth, while he carries his (signet of) jade in his bosom."}
{"label": 0, "text": "To know and yet (think) we do not know is the highest (attainment); not to know (and yet think) we do know is a disease."}
{"label": 0, "text": "It is simply by being pained at (the thought of) having this disease that we are preserved from it."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The sage has not the disease."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He knows the pain that would be inseparable from it, and therefore he does not have it."}
{"label": 0, "text": "When the people do not fear what they ought to fear, that which is their great dread will come on them."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Let them not thoughtlessly indulge themselves in their ordinary life; let them not act as if weary of what that life depends on."}
{"label": 0, "text": "It is by avoiding such indulgence that such weariness does not arise."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore the sage knows (these things) of himself, but does not parade (his knowledge); loves, but does not (appear to set a) value on, himself."}
{"label": 0, "text": "And thus he puts the latter alternative away and makes choice of the former."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He whose boldness appears in his daring (to do wrong, in defiance of the laws) is put to death; he whose boldness appears in his not daring (to do so) lives on."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Of these two cases the one appears to be advantageous, and the other to be injurious."}
{"label": 0, "text": "But When Heaven's anger smites a man, Who the cause shall truly scan?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "On this account the sage feels a difficulty (as to what to do in the former case)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "It is the way of Heaven not to strive, and yet it skilfully overcomes; not to speak, and yet it is skilful in (obtaining a reply; does not call, and yet men come to it of themselves."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Its demonstrations are quiet, and yet its plans are skilful and effective."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The meshes of the net of Heaven are large; far apart, but letting nothing escape."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The people do not fear death; to what purpose is it to (try to) frighten them with death?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "If the people were always in awe of death, and I could always seize those who do wrong, and put them to death, who would dare to do wrong?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "There is always One who presides over the infliction death."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He who would inflict death in the room of him who so presides over it may be described as hewing wood instead of a great carpenter."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Seldom is it that he who undertakes the hewing, instead of the great carpenter, does not cut his own hands!"}
{"label": 0, "text": "The people suffer from famine because of the multitude of taxes consumed by their superiors."}
{"label": 0, "text": "It is through this that they suffer famine."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The people are difficult to govern because of the (excessive) agency of their superiors (in governing them)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "It is through this that they are difficult to govern."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The people make light of dying because of the greatness of their labours in seeking for the means of living."}
{"label": 0, "text": "It is this which makes them think light of dying."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Thus it is that to leave the subject of living altogether out of view is better than to set a high value on it."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Man at his birth is supple and weak; at his death, firm and strong."}
{"label": 0, "text": "(So it is with) all things."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Trees and plants, in their early growth, are soft and brittle; at their death, dry and withered."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Thus it is that firmness and strength are the concomitants of death; softness and weakness, the concomitants of life."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Hence he who (relies on) the strength of his forces does not conquer; and a tree which is strong will fill the out-stretched arms, (and thereby invites the feller.) Therefore the place of what is firm and strong is below, and that of what is soft and weak is above."}
{"label": 0, "text": "May not the Way (or Tao) of Heaven be compared to the (method of) bending a bow?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "The (part of the bow) which was high is brought low, and what was low is raised up."}
{"label": 0, "text": "(So Heaven) diminishes where there is superabundance, and supplements where there is deficiency."}
{"label": 0, "text": "It is the Way of Heaven to diminish superabundance, and to supplement deficiency."}
{"label": 0, "text": "It is not so with the way of man."}
{"label": 0, "text": "He takes away from those who have not enough to add to his own superabundance."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Who can take his own superabundance and therewith serve all under heaven?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "Only he who is in possession of the Tao!"}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore the (ruling) sage acts without claiming the results as his; he achieves his merit and does not rest (arrogantly) in it--he does not wish to display his superiority."}
{"label": 0, "text": "There is nothing in the world more soft and weak than water, and yet for attacking things that are firm and strong there is nothing that can take precedence of it;--for there is nothing (so effectual) for which it can be changed."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Every one in the world knows that the soft overcomes the hard, and the weak the strong, but no one is able to carry it out in practice."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore a sage has said, 'He who accepts his state's reproach, Is hailed therefore its altars' lord; To him who bears men's direful woes They all the name of King accord.' Words that are strictly true seem to be paradoxical."}
{"label": 0, "text": "When a reconciliation is effected (between two parties) after a great animosity, there is sure to be a grudge remaining (in the mind of the one who was wrong)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "And how can this be beneficial (to the other)?"}
{"label": 0, "text": "Therefore (to guard against this), the sage keeps the left-hand portion of the record of the engagement, and does not insist on the (speedy) fulfilment of it by the other party."}
{"label": 0, "text": "(So), he who has the attributes (of the Tao) regards (only) the conditions of the engagement, while he who has not those attributes regards only the conditions favourable to himself."}
{"label": 0, "text": "In the Way of Heaven, there is no partiality of love; it is always on the side of the good man."}
{"label": 0, "text": "In a little state with a small population, I would so order it, that, though there were individuals with the abilities of ten or a hundred men, there should be no employment of them; I would make the people, while looking on death as a grievous thing, yet not remove elsewhere (to avoid it)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Though they had boats and carriages, they should have no occasion to ride in them; though they had buff coats and sharp weapons, they should have no occasion to don or use them."}
{"label": 0, "text": "I would make the people return to the use of knotted cords (instead of the written characters)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "They should think their (coarse) food sweet; their (plain) clothes beautiful; their (poor) dwellings places of rest; and their common (simple) ways sources of enjoyment."}
{"label": 0, "text": "There should be a neighbouring state within sight, and the voices of the fowls and dogs should be heard all the way from it to us, but I would make the people to old age, even to death, not have any intercourse with it."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Sincere words are not fine; fine words are not sincere."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Those who are skilled (in the Tao) do not dispute (about it); the disputatious are not skilled in it."}
{"label": 0, "text": "Those who know (the Tao) are not extensively learned; the extensively learned do not know it."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The sage does not accumulate (for himself)."}
{"label": 0, "text": "The more that he expends for others, the more does he possess of his own; the more that he gives to others, the more does he have himself."}
{"label": 0, "text": "With all the sharpness of the Way of Heaven, it injures not; with all the doing in the way of the sage he does not strive."}
{"label": 1, "text": "All this, whatsoever exists in the universe, should be covered by the Lord."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Having renounced (the unreal), enjoy (the Real)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Do not covet the wealth of any man."}
{"label": 1, "text": "We cover all things with the Lord by perceiving the Divine Presence everywhere."}
{"label": 1, "text": "When the consciousness is firmly fixed in God, the conception of diversity naturally drops away; because the One Cosmic Existence shines through all things."}
{"label": 1, "text": "As we gain the light of wisdom, we cease to cling to the unrealities of this world and we find all our joy in the realm of Reality."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The word enjoy is also interpreted by the great commentator Sankaracharya as protect, because knowledge of our true Self is the greatest protector and sustainer."}
{"label": 1, "text": "If we do not have this knowledge, we cannot be happy; because nothing on this external plane of phenomena is permanent or dependable."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who is rich in the knowledge of the Self does not covet external power or possession."}
{"label": 1, "text": "If one should desire to live in this world a hundred years, one should live performing Karma (righteous deeds)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Thus thou mayest live; there is no other way."}
{"label": 1, "text": "By doing this, Karma (the fruits of thy actions) will not defile thee."}
{"label": 1, "text": "If a man still clings to long life and earthly possessions, and is therefore unable to follow the path of Self-knowledge (Gnana-Nishta) as prescribed in the first Mantram (text), then he may follow the path of right action (Karma-Nishta)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Karma here means actions performed without selfish motive, for the sake of the Lord alone."}
{"label": 1, "text": "When a man performs actions clinging blindly to his lower desires, then his actions bind him to the plane of ignorance or the plane of birth and death; but when the same actions are performed with surrender to God, they purify and liberate him."}
{"label": 1, "text": "After leaving their bodies, they who have killed the Self go to the worlds of the Asuras, covered with blinding ignorance."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The idea of rising to bright regions as a reward for well-doers, and of falling into realms of darkness as a punishment for evil-doers is common to all great religions."}
{"label": 1, "text": "But Vedanta claims that this condition of heaven and hell is only temporary; because our actions, being finite, can produce only a finite result."}
{"label": 1, "text": "What does it mean to kill the Self?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "How can the immortal Soul ever be destroyed?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "It cannot be destroyed, it can only be obscured."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Those who hold themselves under the sway of ignorance, who serve the flesh and neglect the Atman or the real Self, are not able to perceive the effulgent and indestructible nature of their Soul; hence they fall into the realm where the Soul light does not shine."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Here the Upanishad shows that the only hell is absence of knowledge."}
{"label": 1, "text": "As long as man is overpowered by the darkness of ignorance, he is the slave of Nature and must accept whatever comes as the fruit of his thoughts and deeds."}
{"label": 1, "text": "When he strays into the path of unreality, the Sages declare that he destroys himself; because he who clings to the perishable body and regards it as his true Self must experience death many times."}
{"label": 1, "text": "That One, though motionless, is swifter than the mind."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The senses can never overtake It, for It ever goes before."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Though immovable, It travels faster than those who run."}
{"label": 1, "text": "By It the all-pervading air sustains all living beings."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This verse explains the character of the Atman or Self."}
{"label": 1, "text": "A finite object can be taken from one place and put in another, but it can only occupy one space at a time."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The Atman, however, is present everywhere; hence, though one may run with the greatest swiftness to overtake It, already It is there before him."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Even the all-pervading air must be supported by this Self, since It is infinite; and as nothing can live without breathing air, all living things must draw their life from the Cosmic Self."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It moves and It moves not."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is far and also It is near."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is within and also It is without all this."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is near to those who have the power to understand It, for It dwells in the heart of every one; but It seems far to those whose mind is covered by the clouds of sensuality and self-delusion."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is within, because It is the innermost Soul of all creatures; and It is without as the essence of the whole external universe, infilling it like the all-pervading ether."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who sees all beings in the Self and the Self in all beings, he never turns away from It (the Self)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who perceives all beings as the Self for him how can there be delusion or grief, when he sees this oneness (everywhere)?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who perceives the Self everywhere never shrinks from anything, because through his higher consciousness he feels united with all life."}
{"label": 1, "text": "When a man sees God in all beings and all beings in God, and also God dwelling in his own Soul, how can he hate any living thing?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Grief and delusion rest upon a belief in diversity, which leads to competition and all forms of selfishness."}
{"label": 1, "text": "With the realization of oneness, the sense of diversity vanishes and the cause of misery is removed."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He (the Self) is all-encircling, resplendent, bodiless, spotless, without sinews, pure, untouched by sin, all-seeing, all-knowing, transcendent, self-existent; He has disposed all things duly for eternal years."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This text defines the real nature of the Self."}
{"label": 1, "text": "When our mind is cleansed from the dross of matter, then alone can we behold the vast, radiant, subtle, ever-pure and spotless Self, the true basis of our existence."}
{"label": 1, "text": "They enter into blind darkness who worship Avidya (ignorance and delusion); they fall, as it were, into greater darkness who worship Vidya (knowledge)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "By Vidya one end is attained; by Avidya, another."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Thus we have heard from the wise men who taught this."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who knows at the same time both Vidya and Avidya, crosses over death by Avidya and attains immortality through Vidya."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Those who follow or worship the path of selfishness and pleasure (Avidya), without knowing anything higher, necessarily fall into darkness; but those who worship or cherish Vidya (knowledge) for mere intellectual pride and satisfaction, fall into greater darkness, because the opportunity which they misuse is greater."}
{"label": 1, "text": "In the subsequent verses Vidya and Avidya are used in something the same sense as faith and works in the Christian Bible; neither alone can lead to the ultimate goal, but when taken together they carry one to the Highest."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Work done with unselfish motive purifies the mind and enables man to perceive his undying nature."}
{"label": 1, "text": "From this he gains inevitably a knowledge of God, because the Soul and God are one and inseparable; and when he knows himself to be one with the Supreme and Indestructible Whole, he realizes his immortality."}
{"label": 1, "text": "They fall into blind darkness who worship the Unmanifested and they fall into greater darkness who worship the manifested."}
{"label": 1, "text": "By the worship of the Unmanifested one end is attained; by the worship of the manifested, another."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Thus we have heard from the wise men who taught us this."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who knows at the same time both the Unmanifested (the cause of manifestation) and the destructible or manifested, he crosses over death through knowledge of the destructible and attains immortality through knowledge of the First Cause (Unmanifested)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This particular Upanishad deals chiefly with the Invisible Cause and the visible manifestation, and the whole trend of its teaching is to show that they are one and the same, one being the outcome of the other hence no perfect knowledge is possible without simultaneous comprehension of both."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The wise men declare that he who worships in a one-sided way, whether the visible or the invisible, does not reach the highest goal."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Only he who has a co-ordinated understanding of both the visible and the invisible, of matter and spirit, of activity and that which is behind activity, conquers Nature and thus overcomes death."}
{"label": 1, "text": "By work, by making the mind steady and by following the prescribed rules given in the Scriptures, a man gains wisdom."}
{"label": 1, "text": "By the light of that wisdom he is able to perceive the Invisible Cause in all visible forms."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Therefore the wise man sees Him in every manifested form."}
{"label": 1, "text": "They who have a true conception of God are never separated from Him."}
{"label": 1, "text": "They exist in Him and He in them."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The face of Truth is hidden by a golden disk."}
{"label": 1, "text": "O Pushan (Effulgent Being)!"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Uncover (Thy face) that I, the worshipper of Truth, may behold Thee."}
{"label": 1, "text": "O Pushan!"}
{"label": 1, "text": "O Sun, sole traveller of the heavens, controller of all, son of Prajapati, withdraw Thy rays and gather up Thy burning effulgence."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Now through Thy Grace I behold Thy blessed and glorious form."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The Purusha (Effulgent Being) who dwells within Thee, I am He."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Here the sun, who is the giver of all light, is used as the symbol of the Infinite, giver of all wisdom."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The seeker after Truth prays to the Effulgent One to control His dazzling rays, that his eyes, no longer blinded by them, may behold the Truth."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Having perceived It, he proclaims: Now I see that that Effulgent Being and I are one and the same, and my delusion is destroyed."}
{"label": 1, "text": "By the light of Truth he is able to discriminate between the real and the unreal, and the knowledge thus gained convinces him that he is one with the Supreme; that there is no difference between himself and the Supreme Truth; or as Christ said, I and my Father are one."}
{"label": 1, "text": "May my life-breath go to the all-pervading and immortal Prana, and let this body be burned to ashes."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Om!"}
{"label": 1, "text": "O mind, remember thy deeds!"}
{"label": 1, "text": "O mind, remember, remember thy deeds!"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Remember!"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Seek not fleeting results as the reward of thy actions, O mind!"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Strive only for the Imperishable."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This Mantram or text is often chanted at the hour of death to remind one of the perishable nature of the body and the eternal nature of the Soul."}
{"label": 1, "text": "When the clear vision of the distinction between the mortal body and the immortal Soul dawns in the heart, then all craving for physical pleasure or material possession drops away; and one can say, let the body be burned to ashes that the Soul may attain its freedom; for death is nothing more than the casting-off of a worn-out garment."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Vahasrava, being desirous of heavenly rewards (at the Viswajit sacrifice), made a gift of all that he possessed."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He had a son by the name of Nachiketas."}
{"label": 1, "text": "When the offerings were being distributed, faith (Shraddha) entered (the heart of) Nachiketas, who, though young, yet resected:"}
{"label": 1, "text": "These cows have drunk water, eaten grass and given milk for the last time, and their senses have lost all vigour."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who gives these undoubtedly goes to joyless realms."}
{"label": 1, "text": "In India the idea of sacrifice has always been to give freely for the joy of giving, without asking anything in return; and the whole purpose and merit of the sacrifice is lost, if the giver entertains the least thought of name, fame or individual benefit."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The special Viswajit sacrifice which Vajasrava was making required of him to give away all that he possessed."}
{"label": 1, "text": "When, however, the gifts were brought forward to be offered, his son Nachiketas, although probably a lad about twelve years of age, observed how worthless were the animals which his father was offering."}
{"label": 1, "text": "His heart at once became filled with Shraddha."}
{"label": 1, "text": "There is no one English word which can convey the meaning of this Sanskrit term."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is more than mere faith."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It also implies self-reliance, an independent sense of right and wrong, and the courage of one's own conviction."}
{"label": 1, "text": "As a boy of tender age, Nachiketas had no right to question his father's action; yet, impelled by the sudden awakening of his higher nature, he could not but reflect: By merely giving these useless cows, my father cannot gain any merit."}
{"label": 1, "text": "If he has vowed to give all his possessions, then he must also give me."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Otherwise his sacrifice will not be complete and fruitful."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Therefore, anxious for his father's welfare, he approached him gently and reverently."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He said to his father: Dear father, to whom wilt thou give me?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "He said it a second time, then a third time."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The father replied: I shall give thee unto Death."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Nachiketas, being a dutiful son and eager to atone for his father's inadequate sacrifice, tried to remind him thus indirectly that he had not fulfilled his promise to give away all his possessions, since he had not yet offered his own son, who would be a worthier gift than useless cattle."}
{"label": 1, "text": "His father, conscious that he was not making a true sacrifice, tried to ignore the boy's questions; but irritated by his persistence, he at last impatiently made answer: I give thee to Yama, the Lord of Death."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The fact that anger could so quickly rise in his heart proved that he had not the proper attitude of a sacrificer, who must always be tranquil, uplifted and free from egoism."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Nachiketas thought: Among many (of my father's pupils) I stand first; among many (others) I stand in the middle (but never last)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "What will be accomplished for my father by my going this day to Yama?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "It was not conceit which led Nachiketas to consider his own standing and importance."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He was weighing his value as a son and pupil in order to be able to judge whether or not he had merit enough to prove a worthy gift."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Although he realized that his father's harsh reply was only the expression of a momentary outburst of anger; yet he believed that greater harm might befall his father, if his word was not kept."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Therefore he sought to strengthen his father's resolution by reminding him of the transitory condition of life."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He said:"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Look back to those who lived before and look to those who live now."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Like grain the mortal decays and like grain again springs up (is reborn)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "All things perish, Truth alone remains."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Why then fear to sacrifice me also; Thus Nachiketas convinced his father that he should remain true to his word and send him to Yama, the Ruler of Death."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Then Nachiketas went to the abode of Death, but Yama was absent and the boy waited without food or drink for three days."}
{"label": 1, "text": "On Yama's return one of his household said to him:"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Like fire a Brahmana guest enters into houses."}
{"label": 1, "text": "That fire is quenched by an offering."}
{"label": 1, "text": "(Therefore) O Vaivaswata, bring water."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The foolish man in whose house a Brahmana guest remains without food, all his hopes and expectations, all the merit gained by his association with the holy, by his good words and deeds, all his sons and cattle, are destroyed."}
{"label": 1, "text": "According to the ancient Vedic ideal a guest is the representative of God and should be received with due reverence and honor."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Especially is this the case with a Brahmana or a Sannyasin whose life is wholly consecrated to God."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Any one who fails to give proper care to a holy guest brings misfortune on himself and his household."}
{"label": 1, "text": "When Yama returned, therefore, one of the members of his household anxiously informed him of Nachiketas' presence and begged him to bring water to wash his feet, this being always the first service to an arriving guest."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Yama said: O Brahmana!"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Revered guest!"}
{"label": 1, "text": "My salutations to thee."}
{"label": 1, "text": "As thou hast remained three nights in my house without food, therefore choose three boons, O Brahmana."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Nachiketas said: May Gautama, my father, be free from anxious thought (about me)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "May he lose all anger (towards me) and be pacified in heart."}
{"label": 1, "text": "May he know and welcome me when I am sent back by thee."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This, O Death, is the first of the three boons I choose."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Yama replied: Through my will Auddalaki Aruni (thy father) will know thee, and be again towards thee as before."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He will sleep in peace at night."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He will be free from wrath when he sees thee released from the mouth of death."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Nachiketas said: In the realm of heaven there is no fear, thou (Death) art not there; nor is there fear of old age."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Having crossed beyond both hunger and thirst and being above grief, (they) rejoice in heaven."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Thou knowest, O Death, the fire-sacrifice that leads to heaven."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Tell this to me, who am full of Shraddha (faith and yearning)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "They who live in the realm of heaven enjoy freedom from death."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This I beg as my second boon."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Yama replied: I know well that fire which leads to the realm of heaven."}
{"label": 1, "text": "I shall tell it to thee."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Listen to me."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Know, O Nachiketas, that this is the means of attaining endless worlds and their support."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is hidden in the heart of all beings."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Yama then told him that fire-sacrifice, the beginning of all the worlds; what bricks, how many and how laid for the altar."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Nachiketas repeated all as it was told to him."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Then Death, being pleased with him, again said:"}
{"label": 1, "text": "The great-soured Yama, being well pleased, said to him (Nachiketas): I give thee now another boon."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This fire (sacrifice) shall be named after thee."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Take also this garland of many colours."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who performs this Nachiketa fire-sacrifice three times, being united with the three (mother, father and teacher), and who fulfills the three-fold duty (study of the Vedas, sacrifice and alms-giving) crosses over birth and death."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Knowing this worshipful shining fire, born of Brahman, and realizing Him, he attains eternal peace."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who knows the three-fold Nachiketa fire and performs the Nachiketa fire-sacrifice with three-fold knowledge, having cast off the fetters of death and being beyond grief, he rejoices in the realm of heaven."}
{"label": 1, "text": "O Nachiketas, this is thy fire that leads to heaven, which thou hast chosen as thy second boon."}
{"label": 1, "text": "People will call this fire after thy name."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Ask the third boon, Nachiketas."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Fire is regarded as the foundation of all the worlds, because it is the revealer of creation."}
{"label": 1, "text": "If there were no fire or light, no manifested form would be visible."}
{"label": 1, "text": "We read in the Semitic Scriptures, In the beginning the Lord said, 'Let there be light.' Therefore, that which stands in the external universe as one of the purest symbols of the Divine, also dwells in subtle form in the heart of every living being as the vital energy, the life-force or cause of existence."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Yama now tells Nachiketas how, by performing sacrifice with the three-fold knowledge, he may transcend grief and death and reach heaven."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The three-fold knowledge referred to is regarding the preparation of the altar and fire."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Nachiketas being eager to learn, listened with wholehearted attention and was able to repeat all that was told him."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This so pleased Yama that he granted him the extra boon of naming the fire-sacrifice after him and gave him a garland set with precious stones."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Verses XVI-XVIII are regarded by many as an interpolation, which would account for certain obscurities and repetitions in them."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Nachiketas said: There is this doubt regarding what becomes of a man after death."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Some say he exists, others that he does not exist."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This knowledge I desire, being instructed by thee."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Of the boons this is the third boon."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Yama replied: Even the Devas (Bright Ones) of old doubted regarding this."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is not easy to know; subtle indeed is this subject."}
{"label": 1, "text": "O Nachiketas, choose another boon."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Do not press me."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Ask not this boon of me."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Nachiketas said: O Death, thou sayest that even the Devas had doubts about this, and that it is not easy to know."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Another teacher like unto thee is not to be found."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Therefore no other boon can be equal to this one."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Yama said: Ask for sons and grandsons who shall live a hundred years, many cattle, elephants, gold and horses."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Ask for lands of vast extent and live thyself as many autumns as thou desirest."}
{"label": 1, "text": "If thou thinkest of any other boon equal to this, ask for wealth and long life; be ruler over the wide earth."}
{"label": 1, "text": "O Nachiketas, I shall make thee enjoyer of all desires."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Whatsoever objects of desire are difficult to obtain in the realm of mortals, ask them all as thou desirest; these lovely maidens with their chariots and musical instruments, such as are not obtainable by mortals--be served by these whom I give to thee."}
{"label": 1, "text": "O Nachiketas, do not ask regarding death."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The third boon asked by Nachiketas concerning the great Hereafter was one which could be granted only to those who were freed from all mortal desires and limitations, therefore Yama first tested Nachiketas to see whether he was ready to receive such knowledge."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Do not press me regarding this secret, he said."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Even wise men cannot understand it and thou art a mere lad."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Take, rather, long life, wealth, whatever will give thee happiness on the mortal plane."}
{"label": 1, "text": "But the boy proved his strength and worthiness by remaining firm in his resolution to know the great secret of life and death."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Nachiketas said: O Death, these are fleeting; they weaken the vigour of all the senses in man."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Even the longest life is short."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Keep thou thy chariots, dance and music."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Man cannot be satisfied by wealth."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Shall we possess wealth when we see thee (Death)?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Shall we continue to live as long as thou rulest?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Therefore that boon alone is to be chosen by me."}
{"label": 1, "text": "What man dwelling on the decaying mortal plane, having approached the undecaying immortal one, and having reflected upon the nature of enjoyment through beauty and sense pleasure, would delight in long life?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Yama said: The good is one thing and the pleasant another."}
{"label": 1, "text": "These two, having different ends, bind a man."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is well with him who chooses the good."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who chooses the pleasant misses the true end."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The good and the pleasant approach man; the wise examines both and discriminates between them; the wise prefers the good to the pleasant, but the foolish man chooses the pleasant through love of bodily pleasure."}
{"label": 1, "text": "O Nachiketas after wise reflection thou hast renounced the pleasant and all pleasing forms."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Thou hast not accepted this garland of great value for which many mortals perish."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Wide apart are these two,--ignorance and what is known as wisdom, leading in opposite directions."}
{"label": 1, "text": "I believe Nachiketas to be one who longs for wisdom, since many tempting objects have not turned thee aside."}
{"label": 1, "text": "With this second part, the Ruler of Death begins his instructions regarding the great Hereafter."}
{"label": 1, "text": "There are two paths,--one leading Godward, the other leading to worldly pleasure."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who follows one inevitably goes away from the other; because, like light and darkness they conflict."}
{"label": 1, "text": "One leads to the imperishable spiritual realm; the other to the perishable physical realm."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Both confront a man at every step of life."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The discerning man distinguishing between the two, chooses the Real and Eternal, and he alone attains the highest, while the ignorant man, preferring that which brings him immediate and tangible results, misses the true purpose of his existence."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Although Yama put before Nachiketas many temptations to test his sincerity and earnestness, he judging them at their real value, refused them all, saying I have come from the mortal realm, shall I ask for what is mortal?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "I desire only that which is eternal."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Then Death said to him: I now see that thou art a sincere desirer of Truth."}
{"label": 1, "text": "I offered thee vast wealth, long life and every form of pleasure which tempts and deludes men; but thou hast proved thy worthiness by rejecting them all."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Fools dwelling in ignorance, yet imagining themselves wise and learned, go round and round in crooked ways, like the blind led by the blind."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The Hereafter never rises before the thoughtless child (the ignorant), deluded by the glamour of wealth."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This world alone is, there is none other: thinking thus, he falls under my sway again and again."}
{"label": 1, "text": "There are many in the world, who, puffed up with intellectual conceit, believe that they are capable of guiding others."}
{"label": 1, "text": "But although they may possess a certain amount of worldly wisdom, they are devoid of deeper understanding; therefore all that they say merely increases doubt and confusion in the minds of those who hear them."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Hence they are likened to blind men leading the blind."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The Hereafter does not shine before those who are lacking in the power of discrimination and are easily carried away therefore by the charm of fleeting objects."}
{"label": 1, "text": "As children are tempted by toys, so they are tempted by pleasure, power, name and fame."}
{"label": 1, "text": "To them these seem the only realities."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Being thus attached to perishable things, they come many times under the dominion of death."}
{"label": 1, "text": "There is one part of us which must die; there is another part which never dies."}
{"label": 1, "text": "When a man can identify himself with his undying nature, which is one with God, then he overcomes death."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He about whom many are not even able to hear, whom many cannot comprehend even after hearing: wonderful is the teacher, wonderful is he who can receive when taught by an able teacher."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Throughout the Vedic Scriptures it is declared that no one can impart spiritual knowledge unless he has realization."}
{"label": 1, "text": "What is meant by realization?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "It means knowledge based on direct perception."}
{"label": 1, "text": "In India often the best teachers have no learning, but their character is so shining that every one learns merely by coming in contact with them."}
{"label": 1, "text": "In one of the Scriptures we read: Under a banyan tree sat a youthful teacher and beside him an aged disciple."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The mind of the disciple was full of doubts and questions, but although the teacher continued silent, gradually every doubt vanished from the disciple's mind."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This signifies that the conveying of spiritual teaching does not depend upon words only."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is the life, the illumination, which counts."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Such God-enlightened men, however, cannot easily be found; but even with such a teacher, the knowledge of the Self cannot be gained unless the heart of the disciple is open and ready for the Truth."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Hence Yama says both teacher and taught must be wonderful."}
{"label": 1, "text": "When taught by a man of inferior understanding, this Atman cannot be truly known, even though frequently thought upon."}
{"label": 1, "text": "There is no way (to know It) unless it is taught by another (an illumined teacher), for it is subtler than the subtle and beyond argument."}
{"label": 1, "text": "O Dearest, this Atman cannot be attained by argument; It is truly known only when taught by another (a wise teacher)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "O Nachiketas, thou hast attained It."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Thou art fixed in Truth."}
{"label": 1, "text": "May we ever, find a questioner like thee."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Knowledge of the Atman or Self cannot be attained when it is taught by those who themselves lack in real understanding of It; and who therefore, having no definite conviction of their own, differ among themselves as to its nature and existence."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Only he who has been able to perceive the Self directly, through the unfoldment of his higher nature, can proclaim what It actually is; and his words alone carry weight and bring illumination."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is too subtle to be reached by argument."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This secret regarding the Hereafter cannot be known through reasoning or mere intellectual gymnastics."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is to be attained only in a state of consciousness which transcends the boundary line of reason."}
{"label": 1, "text": "I know that (earthly) treasure is transitory, for the eternal can never be attained by things which are non-eternal."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Hence the Nachiketa fire (sacrifice) has been performed by me with perishable things and yet I have attained the eternal."}
{"label": 1, "text": "O Nachiketas, thou hast seen the fulfillment of all desires, the basis of the universe, the endless fruit of sacrificial rites, the other shore where there is no fear, that which is praiseworthy, the great and wide support; yet, being wise, thou hast rejected all with firm resolve."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The teacher, saying that the imperishable cannot be attained by the perishable, shows that no amount of observance of rituals and ceremonies can earn the imperishable and eternal."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Although the Nachiketa fire-sacrifice may bring results which seem eternal to mortals because of their long duration, yet they too must come to an end; therefore this sacrifice cannot lead to the final goal."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Yama praises Nachiketas because, when all heavenly and earthly pleasures, as well as knowledge of all realms and their enjoyments were offered him, yet he cast them aside and remained firm in his desire for Truth alone."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The wise, who by means of the highest meditation on the Self knows the Ancient One, difficult to perceive, seated in the innermost recess, hidden in the cave of the heart, dwelling in the depth of inner being, (he who knows that One) as God, is liberated from the fetters of joy and sorrow."}
{"label": 1, "text": "A mortal, having heard and fully grasped this, and having realized through discrimination the subtle Self, rejoices, because he has obtained that which is the source of all joy."}
{"label": 1, "text": "I think the abode (of Truth) is open to Nachiketas."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The Scriptures give three stages in all spiritual attainment."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The aspirant must first hear about the Truth from an enlightened teacher; next he must reflect upon what he has heard; then by constant practice of discrimination and meditation he realizes it; and with realization comes the fulfilment of every desire, because it unites him with the source of all."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Having beheld this, a man learns that all sense pleasures are but fragmentary reflections of that one supreme joy, which can be found in the true Self alone."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Yama assures Nachiketas that there is no doubt of his realizing the Truth, because he has shown the highest discrimination as well as fixity of purpose."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Nachiketas said: That which thou seest, which is neither virtue nor vice, neither cause nor effect, neither past nor future (but beyond these), tell me That."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Yama replied: That goal which all the Vedas glorify, which all austerities proclaim, desiring which (people) practice Brahmacharya (a life of continence and service), that goal I tell thee briefly--it is Aum."}
{"label": 1, "text": "What name can man give to God?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "How can the Infinite be bound by any finite word?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "All that language can express must be finite, since it is itself finite."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Yet it is very difficult for mortals to think or speak of anything without calling it by a definite name."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Knowing this, the Sages gave to the Supreme the name A-U-M which stands as the root of all language."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The first letter A is the mother-sound, being the natural sound uttered by every creature when the throat is opened, and no sound can be made without opening the throat."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The last letter M, spoken by closing the lips, terminates all articulation."}
{"label": 1, "text": "As one carries the sound from the throat to the lips, it passes through the sound U."}
{"label": 1, "text": "These three sounds therefore cover the whole field of possible articulate sound."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Their combination is called the Akshara or the imperishable word, the Sound-Brahman or the Word God, because it is the most universal name which can be given to the Supreme."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Hence it must be the word which was in the beginning and corresponds to the Logos of Christian theology."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is because of the all-embracing significance of this name that it is used so universally in the Vedic Scriptures to designate the Absolute."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This Word is indeed Brahman."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This Word is indeed the Supreme."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who knows this Word obtains whatever he desires."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This is the best Support, This is the highest Support; he who knows this Support is glorified in the world of Brahman."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This sacred Word is the highest symbol of the Absolute."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who through meditating on It grasps Its full significance, realizes the glory of God and at once has all his desires satisfied, because God is the fulfilment of all desires."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This Self is never born, nor does It die."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It did not spring from anything, nor did anything spring from It."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This Ancient One is unborn, eternal, everlasting."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is not slain even though the body is slain."}
{"label": 1, "text": "If the slayer thinks that he slays, or if the slain thinks that he is slain, both of these know not."}
{"label": 1, "text": "For It neither slays nor is It slain."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The Self is subtler than the subtle, greater than the great; It dwells in the heart of each living being."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who is free from desire and free from grief, with mind and senses tranquil, beholds the glory of the Atman."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Although this Atman dwells in the heart of every living being, yet It is not perceived by ordinary mortals because of Its subtlety."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It cannot be perceived by the senses; a finer spiritual sight is required."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The heart must be pure and freed from every unworthy selfish desire; the thought must be indrawn from all external objects; mind and body must be under control; when the whole being thus becomes calm and serene, then it is possible to perceive that effulgent Atman."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is subtler than the subtle, because It is the invisible essence of every thing; and It is greater than the great because It is the boundless, sustaining power of the whole universe; that upon which all existence rests."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Though sitting, It travels far; though lying, It goes everywhere."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Who else save me is fit to know that God, who is (both) joyful and joyless?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "The Self is all-pervading, hence It is that which sits still and that which travels, that which is active and that which is inactive."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is both stationary and moving, and It is the basis of all forms of existence; therefore whatever exists in the universe, whether joy or joylessness, pleasure or pain, must spring from It."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Who is better able to know God than I myself, since He resides in my heart and is the very essence of my being?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Such should be the attitude of one who is seeking."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The wise who know the Self, bodiless, seated within perishable bodies, great and all- pervading, grieve not."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Then a wise man through the practice of discrimination has seen clearly the distinction between body and Soul, he knows that his true Self is not the body, though It dwells in the body."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Thus realizing the indestructible, all-pervading nature of his real Self, he surmounts all fear of death or loss, and is not moved even by the greatest sorrow."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This Self cannot be attained by study of the Scriptures, nor by intellectual perception, nor by frequent hearing (of It); He whom the Self chooses, by him alone is It attained."}
{"label": 1, "text": "To him the Self reveals Its true nature."}
{"label": 1, "text": "We may imagine that by much study we can find out God; but merely hearing about a thing and gaining an intellectual comprehension of it does not mean attaining true knowledge of it."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Knowledge only comes through direct perception, and direct perception of God is possible for those alone who are pure in heart and spiritually awakened."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Although He is alike to all beings and His mercy is on all, yet the impure and worldy-minded do not get the blessing, because they do not know how to open their hearts to it."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who longs for God, him the Lord chooses; because to him alone can He reveal His true nature."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who has not turned away from evil conduct, whose senses are uncontrolled, who is not tranquil, whose mind is not at rest, he can never attain this Atman even by knowledge."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Yama having first described what the Atman is, now tells us how to attain It."}
{"label": 1, "text": "A man must try to subdue his lower nature and gain control over the body and senses."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He must conquer the impure selfish desires which now disturb the serenity of his mind, that it may grow calm and peaceful."}
{"label": 1, "text": "In other words, he must live the life and develop all spiritual qualities in order to perceive the Atman."}
{"label": 1, "text": "There are two who enjoy the fruits of their good deeds in the world, having entered into the cave of the heart, seated (there) on the highest summit."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The knowers of Brahman call them shadow and light."}
{"label": 1, "text": "So also (they are called) by householders who perform five fire- sacrifices or three Nachiketa fire-sacrifices."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Here the two signify the Higher Self and the lower self, dwelling in the innermost cave of the heart."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The Seers of Truth, as well as householders who follow the path of rituals and outer forms with the hope of enjoying the fruits of their good deeds, both proclaim that the Higher Self is like a light and the lower self like a shadow."}
{"label": 1, "text": "When the Truth shines clearly in the heart of the knower, then he surmounts the apparent duality of his nature and becomes convinced that there is but One, and that all outer manifestations are nothing but reflections or projections of that One."}
{"label": 1, "text": "May we be able to learn that Nachiketa fire-sacrifice, which is a bridge for those who perform sacrifice."}
{"label": 1, "text": "May we also know the One, who is the highest imperishable Brahman for those who desire to cross over to the other shore which is beyond fear."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The significance of this text is May we acquire the knowledge of Brahman, the Supreme, in both manifested and unmanifested form."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He is manifested as the Lord of sacrifice for those who follow the path of ritual."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He is the unmanifested, eternal, universal Supreme Being for those who follow the path of wisdom."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The other shore, being the realm of immortality, is said to be beyond fear; because disease, death, and all that which mortals fear, cease to exist there."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is believed by many that these two opening verses were a later interpolation."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Know the Atman (Self) as the lord of the chariot, and the body as the chariot."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Know also the intellect to be the driver and mind the reins."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The senses are called the horses; the sense objects are the roads; when the Atman is united with body, senses and mind, then the wise call Him the enjoyer."}
{"label": 1, "text": "In the third chapter Yama defines what part of our being dies and what part is deathless, what is mortal and what is immortal."}
{"label": 1, "text": "But the Atman, the Higher Self, is so entirely beyond human conception that it is impossible to give a direct definition of It."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Only through similies can some idea of It be conveyed."}
{"label": 1, "text": "That is the reason why all the great Teachers of the world have so often taught in the form of parables."}
{"label": 1, "text": "So here the Ruler of Death represents the Self as the lord of this chariot of the body."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The intellect or discriminative faculty is the driver, who controls these wild horses of the senses by holding firmly the reins of the mind."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The roads over which these horses travel are made up of all the external objects which attract or repel the senses:--the sense of smelling follows the path of sweet odours, the sense of seeing the way of beautiful sights."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Thus each sense, unless restrained by the discriminative faculty, seeks to go out towards its special objects."}
{"label": 1, "text": "When the Self is joined with body, mind and senses, It is called the intelligent enjoyer; because It is the one who wills, feels, perceives and does everything."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who is without discrimination and whose mind is always uncontrolled, his senses are unmanageable, like the vicious horses of a driver."}
{"label": 1, "text": "But he who is full of discrimination and whose mind is always controlled, his senses are manageable, like the good horses of a driver."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The man whose intellect is not discriminative and who fails to distinguish right from wrong, the real from the unreal, is carried away by his sense passions and desires, just as a driver is carried away by vicious horses over which he has lost control."}
{"label": 1, "text": "But he who clearly distinguishes what is good from what is merely pleasant, and controls all his out-going forces from running after apparent momentary pleasures, his senses obey and serve him as good horses obey their driver."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who does not possess discrimination, whose mind is uncontrolled and always impure, he does not reach that goal, but falls again into Samsara (realm of birth and death)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "But he who possesses right discrimination, whose mind is under control and always pure, he reaches that goal, from which he is not born again."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The man who has a discriminative intellect for the driver, and a controlled mind for the reins, reaches the end of the journey, the highest place of Vishnu (the All-pervading and Unchangeable One)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "A driver must possess first a thorough knowledge of the road; next he must understand how to handle the reins and control his horses."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Then will he drive safely to his destination."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Similarly in this journey of life, our mind and senses must be wholly under the control of our higher discriminative faculty; for only when all our forces work in unison can we hope to reach the goal--the abode of Absolute Truth."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Beyond the senses are the objects, beyond the objects is the mind, beyond the mind is the intellect, beyond the intellect is the great Atman."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Beyond the great Atman is the Unmanifested; beyond the Unmanifested is the Purusha (the Cosmic Soul); beyond the Purusha there is nothing."}
{"label": 1, "text": "That is the end, that is the final goal."}
{"label": 1, "text": "In these two verses the Teacher shows the process of discrimination, by which one attains knowledge of the subtle Self."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Beginning with the sense-organs, he leads up to the less and less gross, until he reaches that which is subtlest of all, the true Self of man."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The senses are dependent on sense-objects, because without these the senses would have no utility."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Superior to sense-objects is the mind, because unless these objects affect the mind, they cannot influence the senses."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Over the mind the determinative faculty exercises power; this determinative faculty is governed by the individual Self; beyond this Self is the undifferentiated creative energy known as Avyaktam; and above this is the Purusha or Supreme Self."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Than this there is nothing higher."}
{"label": 1, "text": "That is the goal, the Highest Abode of Peace and Bliss."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This Atman (Self), hidden in all beings, does not shine forth; but It is seen by subtle seers through keen and subtle understanding."}
{"label": 1, "text": "If It dwells in all living beings, why do we not see It?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Because the ordinary man's vision is too dull and distracted."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is visible to those alone whose intellect has been purified by constant thought on the Supreme, and whose sight therefore has become refined and sharpened."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This keenness of vision comes only when all our forces have been made one-pointed through steadfast practice of concentration and meditation."}
{"label": 1, "text": "A wise man should control speech by mind, mind by intellect, intellect by the great Atman, and that by the Peaceful One (the Paramatman or Supreme Self)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Here Yama gives the practical method to be followed if one wishes to realize the Supreme."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The word speech stands for all the senses."}
{"label": 1, "text": "First, therefore, a man must control his outgoing senses by the mind."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Then the mind must be brought under the control of the discriminative faculty; that is, it must be withdrawn from all sense-objects and cease to waste its energies on nonessential things."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The discriminative faculty in turn must be controlled by the higher individual intelligence and this must be governed wholly by the Supreme Intelligence."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Arise!"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Awake!"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Having reached the Great Ones (illumined Teachers), gain understanding."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The path is as sharp as a razor, impassable and difficult to travel, so the wise declare."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This is the eternal call of the wise: Awake from the slumber of ignorance!"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Arise and seek out those who know the Truth, because only those who have direct vision of Truth are capable of teaching It."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Invoke their blessing with a humble spirit and seek to be instructed by them."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The path is very difficult to tread."}
{"label": 1, "text": "No thoughtless or lethargic person can safely travel on it."}
{"label": 1, "text": "One must be strong, wakeful and persevering."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Knowing That which is soundless, touchless, formless, undecaying; also tasteless, odorless, and eternal; beginningless, endless and immutable; beyond the Unmanifested: (knowing That) man escapes from the mouth of death."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The Ruler of Death defines here the innermost essence of our being."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Because of its extreme subtlety, it cannot be heard or felt or smelled or tasted like any ordinary object."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It never dies."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It has no beginning or end."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is unchangeable."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Realizing this Supreme Reality, man escapes from death and attains everlasting life."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Thus the Teacher has gradually led Nachiketas to a point where he can reveal to him the secret of death."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The boy had thought that there was a place where he could stay and become immortal."}
{"label": 1, "text": "But Yama shows him that immortality is a state of consciousness and is not gained so long as man clings to name and form, or to perishable objects."}
{"label": 1, "text": "What dies?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Form."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Therefore the formful man dies; but not that which dwells within."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Although inconceivably subtle, the Sages have always made an effort through similies and analogies to give some idea of this inner Self or the God within."}
{"label": 1, "text": "They have described It as beyond mind and speech; too subtle for ordinary perception, but not beyond the range of purified vision."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The intelligent man, who has heard and repeated the ancient story of Nachiketas, told by the Ruler of Death, is glorified in the world of Brahman."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The Self-existent created the senses out-going; for this reason man sees the external, but not the inner Atman (Self)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Some wise man, however, desiring immortality, with eyes turned away (from the external) sees the Atman within."}
{"label": 1, "text": "In the last chapter the Ruler of Death instructed Nachiketas regarding the nature and glory of the Self."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Now he shows the reason why the Self is not seen by the majority."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is because man's mind is constantly drawn outward through the channels of his senses, and this prevents his seeing the inner Self (Pratyagatman); but now and then a seeker, wiser than others, goes within and attains the vision of the undying Self."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Children (the ignorant) pursue external pleasures; (thus) they fall into the wide- spread snare of death."}
{"label": 1, "text": "But the wise, knowing the nature of immortality, do not seek the permanent among fleeting things."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Those who are devoid of discrimination and fail to distinguish between real and unreal, the fleeting and the permanent, set their hearts on the changeable things of this world; hence they entangle themselves in the net of insatiable desire, which leads inevitably to disappointment and suffering."}
{"label": 1, "text": "To such, death must seem a reality because they identify themselves with that which is born and which dies."}
{"label": 1, "text": "But the wise, who see deeper into the nature of things, are no longer deluded by the charm of the phenomenal world and do not seek for permanent happiness among its passing enjoyments."}
{"label": 1, "text": "That by which one knows form, taste, smell, sound, touch and sense enjoyments, by That also one knows whatever remains (to be known)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This verily is That (which thou hast asked to know)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "That by which a mortal perceives, both in dream and in waking, by knowing that great all-pervading Atman the wise man grieves no more."}
{"label": 1, "text": "In these verses the teacher tries to make plain that all knowledge, as well as all sense perception, in every state of consciousness--sleeping, dreaming or waking--is possible only because the Self exists."}
{"label": 1, "text": "There can be no knowledge or perception independent of the Self."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Wise men, aware of this, identify themselves with their Higher Self and thus transcend the realm of grief."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who knows this Atman, the honey-eater (perceiver and enjoyer of objects), ever near, as the lord of the past and future, fears no more."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This verily is That."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who sees Him seated in the five elements, born of Tapas (fire of Brahman), born before water; who, having entered the cave of the heart, abides therein --this verily is That."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This verse indicates that He, the Great Self, is the cause of all created objects."}
{"label": 1, "text": "According to the Vedas, His first manifestation was Brahma, the Personal God or Creator, born of the fire of wisdom."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He existed before the evolution of the five elements-- earth, water, fire, air and ether; hence He was born before water."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He is the Self dwelling in the hearts of all creatures."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who knows Aditi, who rises with Prana (the Life Principle), existent in all the Devas; who, having entered into the heart, abides there; and who was born from the elements--this verily is That."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This verse is somewhat obscure and seems like an interpolated amplification of the preceding verse."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The all-seeing fire which exists hidden in the two sticks, as the foetus is well-guarded in the womb by the mother, (that fire) is to be worshipped day after day by wakeful seekers (after wisdom), as well as by sacrificers."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This verily is That."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Fire is called all-seeing because its light makes everything visible."}
{"label": 1, "text": "In Vedic sacrifices the altar fire was always kindled by rubbing together two sticks of a special kind of wood called Arani."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Because fire was regarded as one of the most perfect symbols of Divine wisdom, it was to be worshipped by all seekers after Truth, whether they followed the path of meditation or the path of rituals."}
{"label": 1, "text": "From whence the sun rises, and whither it goes at setting, upon That all the Devas depend."}
{"label": 1, "text": "No one goes beyond That."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This verily is That."}
{"label": 1, "text": "What is here (in the visible world), that is there (in the invisible); he who sees difference (between visible and invisible) goes from death to death."}
{"label": 1, "text": "By mind alone this is to be realized."}
{"label": 1, "text": "There is no difference whatever (between visible and invisible)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who sees difference here (between these) goes from death to death."}
{"label": 1, "text": "In the sight of true wisdom, there is no difference between the creator and the created."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Even physical science has come to recognize that cause and effect are but two aspects of one manifestation of energy."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who fails to see this, being engrossed in the visible only, goes from death to death; because he clings to external forms which are perishable."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Only the essence which dwells within is unchangeable and imperishable."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This knowledge of the oneness of visible and invisible, however, cannot be acquired through sense-perception."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It can only be attained by the purified mind."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The Purusha (Self), of the size of a thumb, resides in the middle of the body as the lord of the past and the future, (he who knows Him) fears no more."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This verily is That."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The seat of the Purusha is said to be the heart, hence It resides in the middle of the body."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Although It is limitless and all-pervading, yet in relation to Its abiding-place It is represented as limited in extension, the size of a thumb."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This refers really to the heart, which in shape may be likened to a thumb."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Its light is everywhere, yet we see it focused in a lamp and believe it to be there only; similarly, although the life-current flows everywhere in the body, the heart is regarded as peculiarly its seat."}
{"label": 1, "text": "That Purusha, of the size of a thumb, is like a light without smoke, lord of the past and the future."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He is the same today and tomorrow."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This verily is That."}
{"label": 1, "text": "In this verse the teacher defines the effulgent nature of the Soul, whose light is pure like a flame without smoke."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He also answers the question put by Nachiketas as to what happens after death, by declaring that no real change takes place, because the Soul is ever the same."}
{"label": 1, "text": "As rain water, (falling) on the mountain top, runs down over the rocks on all sides; similarly, he who sees difference (between visible forms) runs after them in various directions."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The city of the Unborn, whose knowledge is unchanging, has eleven gates."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Thinking on Him, man grieves no more; and being freed (from ignorance), he attains liberation."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This verily is That."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This human body is called a city with eleven gates, where the eternal unborn Spirit dwells."}
{"label": 1, "text": "These gates are the two eyes, two ears, two nostrils, the mouth, the navel, the two lower apertures, and the imperceptible opening at the top of the head."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The Self or Atman holds the position of ruler in this city; and being above the modifications of birth, death and all human imperfections, It is not affected by the changes of the physical organism."}
{"label": 1, "text": "As the intelligent man through constant thought and meditation realizes the splendour of this Supreme Spirit, he becomes free from that part of his nature which grieves and suffers, and thus he attains liberation."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He is the sun dwelling in the bright heaven; He is the air dwelling in space; He is the fire burning on the altar; He is the guest dwelling in the house."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He dwells in man."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He dwells in those greater than man."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He dwells in sacrifice."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He dwells in the ether."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He is (all that is) born in water, (all that) is born in earth, (all that) is born in sacrifice, (all that) is born on mountains."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He is the True and the Great."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He it is who sends the (in-coming) Prana (life-breath) upward and throws the (out-going) breath downward."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Him all the senses worship, the adorable Atman, seated in the centre (the heart)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "When this Atman, which is seated in the body, goes out (from the body), what remains then?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "This verily is That."}
{"label": 1, "text": "No mortal lives by the in-coming breath (Prana) or by the out-going breath (Apana), but he lives by another on which these two depend."}
{"label": 1, "text": "O Gautama (Nachiketas), I shall declare unto thee the secret of the eternal Brahman and what happens to the Self after death."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Some Jivas (individual Souls) enter wombs to be embodied; others go into immovable forms, according to their deeds and knowledge."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This text shows the application of the law of cause and effect to all forms of life."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The thoughts and actions of the present life determine the future birth and environment."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The Being who remains awake while all sleep, who grants all desires, That is pure, That is Brahman, That alone is said to be immortal."}
{"label": 1, "text": "On That all the worlds rest."}
{"label": 1, "text": "None goes beyond That."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This verily is That."}
{"label": 1, "text": "As fire, though one, having entered the world, becomes various according to what it burns, so does the Atman (Self) within all living beings, though one, become various according to what it enters."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It also exists outside."}
{"label": 1, "text": "As air, though one, having entered the world, becomes various according to what it enters, so does the Atman within all living beings, though one, become various according to what it enters."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It also exists outside."}
{"label": 1, "text": "By using these similies of fire and air, the teacher tries to show Nachiketas the subtle quality of the great Self, who, although one and formless like air and fire, yet assumes different shapes according to the form in which It dwells."}
{"label": 1, "text": "But, being all-pervading and unlimited, It cannot be confined to these forms; therefore it is said that It also exists outside all forms."}
{"label": 1, "text": "As the sun, the eye of the whole world, is not defiled by external impurities seen by the eyes, thus the one inner Self of all living beings is not defiled by the misery of the world, being outside it."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The sun is called the eye of the world because it reveals all objects."}
{"label": 1, "text": "As the sun may shine on the most impure object, yet remain uncontaminated by it, so the Divine Self within is not touched by the impurity or suffering of the physical form in which it dwells, the Self being beyond all bodily limitations."}
{"label": 1, "text": "There is one ruler, the Self of all living beings, who makes the one form manifold; the wise who perceive Him seated within their Self, to them belongs eternal bliss, not to others."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Eternal among the changing, consciousness of the conscious, who, though one, fulfils the desires of many: the wise who perceive Him seated within their Self, to them belongs eternal peace, not to others."}
{"label": 1, "text": "They (the wise) perceive that indescribable highest bliss, saying, This is That."}
{"label": 1, "text": "How am I to know It?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Does It shine (by Its own light) or does It shine (by reflected light)?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "This ancient Aswattha tree has its root above and branches below."}
{"label": 1, "text": "That is pure, That is Brahman, That alone is called the Immortal."}
{"label": 1, "text": "All the worlds rest in That."}
{"label": 1, "text": "None goes beyond That."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This verily is That."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This verse indicates the origin of the tree of creation (the Samsara-Vriksha), which is rooted above in Brahman, the Supreme, and sends its branches downward into the phenomenal world."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Heat and cold, pleasure and pain, birth and death, and all the shifting conditions of the mortal realm--these are the branches; but the origin of the tree, the Brahman, is eternally pure, unchanging, free and deathless."}
{"label": 1, "text": "From the highest angelic form to the minutest atom, all created things have their origin in Him."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He is the foundation of the universe."}
{"label": 1, "text": "There is nothing beyond Him."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Whatever there is in the universe is evolved from Prana and vibrates in Prana."}
{"label": 1, "text": "That is a mighty terror, like an upraised thunderbolt."}
{"label": 1, "text": "They who know That become immortal."}
{"label": 1, "text": "From fear of Him the fire burns, from fear of Him the sun shines."}
{"label": 1, "text": "From fear of Him Indra and Vayu and Death, the fifth, speed forth."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Just as the body cannot live or act without the Soul, similarly nothing in the created world can exist independent of Brahman, who is the basis of all existence."}
{"label": 1, "text": "His position is like that of a king whom all must obey; hence it is said that the gods of sun, moon, wind, rain, do His bidding."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He is likened to an upraised thunderbolt, because of the impartial and inevitable nature of His law, which all powers, great or small, must obey absolutely."}
{"label": 1, "text": "If a man is not able to know Him before the dissolution of the body, then he becomes embodied again in the created worlds."}
{"label": 1, "text": "As soon as a man acquires knowledge of the Supreme, he is liberated; but if he fails to attain such knowledge before his Soul is separated from the body, then he must take other bodies and return again and again to this realm of birth and death, until through varied experience he realizes the nature of the Supreme and his relation to Him."}
{"label": 1, "text": "As in a mirror, so is He seen within oneself; as in a dream, so (is He seen) in the world of the fathers (departed spirits); as in water, so (is He seen) in the world of Gandharvas (the angelic realm)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "As light and shadow, so (is He seen) in the world of Brahma (the Creator)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "When by means of a purified understanding one beholds God within, the image is distinct as in a polished mirror; but one cannot have clear vision of the Supreme by attaining to the various realms known as heavens, where one reaps the fruit of his good deeds."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is only by developing one's highest consciousness here in this life that perfect God-vision can be attained."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Knowing that the senses are distinct (from the Atman) and their rising and setting separate (from the Atman), a wise man grieves no more."}
{"label": 1, "text": "A wise man never confounds the Atman, which is birthless and deathless, with that which has beginning and end."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Therefore, when he sees his senses and his physical organism waxing and waning, he knows that his real Self within can never be affected by these outer changes, so he remains unmoved."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Higher than the senses is the mind, higher than the mind is the intellect, higher than the intellect is the great Atman, higher than the Atman is the Unmanifested."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Beyond the Unmanifested is the all-pervading and imperceptible Being (Purusha)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "By knowing Him, the mortal is liberated and attains immortality."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This division of the individual into senses, mind, intellect, self-consciousness, undifferentiated creative energy and the Absolute Self is explained in the commentary of verse XI, Part Third."}
{"label": 1, "text": "His form is not to be seen."}
{"label": 1, "text": "No one can see Him with the eye."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He is perceived by the heart, by the intellect and by the mind."}
{"label": 1, "text": "They who know this become immortal."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The Supreme, being formless, cannot be discerned by the senses, hence all knowledge of Him must be acquired by the subtler faculties of heart, intellect and mind, which are developed only through the purifying practice of meditation."}
{"label": 1, "text": "When the five organs of perception become still, together with the mind, and the intellect ceases to be active: that is called the highest state."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The teacher now shows Nachiketas the process by which the transcendental vision can be attained."}
{"label": 1, "text": "he out-going senses,--seeing, hearing, smelling, touching, tasting; the restless mind and the intellect: all must be indrawn and quieted."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The state of equilibrium thus attained is called the highest state, because all the forces of one's being become united and focused; and this inevitably leads to supersensuous vision."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This firm holding back of the senses is what is known as Yoga."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Then one should become watchful, for Yoga comes and goes."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Yoga literally means to join or to unite the lower self with the Higher Self, the object with the subject, the worshipper with God."}
{"label": 1, "text": "In order to gain this union, however, one must first disunite oneself from all that scatters the physical, mental and intellectual forces; so the outgoing perceptions must be detached from the external world and indrawn."}
{"label": 1, "text": "When this is accomplished through constant practice of concentration and meditation, the union takes place of its own accord."}
{"label": 1, "text": "But it may be lost again, unless one is watchful."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He cannot be attained by speech, by mind, or by the eye."}
{"label": 1, "text": "How can That be realized except by him who says He is?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "He should be realized as He is and also as the reality of both (visible and invisible)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who knows Him as He is, to him alone His real nature is revealed."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This supersensuous vision cannot be gained through man's ordinary faculties."}
{"label": 1, "text": "By mind, eye, or speech the manifested attributes of the Divine can be apprehended; but only one who has acquired the supersensuous sight can directly perceive God's existence and declare definitely that He is, that He alone exists in both the visible and the invisible world."}
{"label": 1, "text": "When all desires dwelling in the heart cease, then the mortal becomes immortal and attains Brahman here."}
{"label": 1, "text": "When all the ties of the heart are cut asunder here, then the mortal becomes immortal."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Such is the teaching."}
{"label": 1, "text": "There are a hundred and one nerves of the heart."}
{"label": 1, "text": "One of them penetrates the centre of the head."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Going upward through it, one attains immortality."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The other (hundred nerve-courses) lead, in departing, to different worlds."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The nervous system of the body provides the channels through which the mind travels; the direction in which it moves is determined by its desires and tendencies."}
{"label": 1, "text": "When the mind becomes pure and desireless, it takes the upward course and at the time of departing passes out through the imperceptible opening at the crown of the head; but as long as it remains full of desires, its course is downward towards the realms where those desires can be satisfied."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The Purusha, the inner Self, of the size of a thumb, is ever seated in the heart of all living beings."}
{"label": 1, "text": "With perseverance man should draw Him out from his body as one draws the inner stalk from a blade of grass."}
{"label": 1, "text": "One should know Him as pure and deathless, as pure and deathless."}
{"label": 1, "text": "As has been explained in Part Fourth, verse XII, the inner Self, although unlimited, is described as the size of a thumb because of its abiding-place in the heart, often likened to a lotus-bud which is similar to a thumb in size and shape."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Through the process of steadfast discrimination, one should learn to differentiate the Soul from the body, just as one separates the pith from a reed."}
{"label": 1, "text": "By whom commanded and directed does the mind go towards its objects?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Commanded by whom does the life-force, the first (cause), move?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "At whose will do men utter speech?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "What power directs the eye and the ear?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Thus the disciple approached the Master and inquired concerning the cause of life and human activity."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Having a sincere longing for Truth he desired to know who really sees and hears, who actuates the apparent physical man."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He perceived all about him the phenomenal world, the existence of which he could prove by his senses; but he sought to know the invisible causal world, of which he was now only vaguely conscious."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Is mind all-pervading and all-powerful, or is it impelled by some other force, he asked."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Who sends forth the vital energy, without which nothing can exist?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "The teacher replies:"}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is the ear of the ear, the mind of the mind, the speech of the speech, the life of the life, the eye of the eye."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The wise, freed (from the senses and from mortal desires), after leaving this world, become immortal."}
{"label": 1, "text": "An ordinary man hears, sees, thinks, but he is satisfied to know only as much as can be known through the senses; he does not analyze and try to find that which stands behind the ear or eye or mind."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He is completely identified with his external nature."}
{"label": 1, "text": "His conception does not go beyond the little circle of his bodily life, which concerns the outer man only."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He has no consciousness of that which enables his senses and organs to perform their tasks."}
{"label": 1, "text": "There is a vast difference between the manifested form and That which is manifested through the form."}
{"label": 1, "text": "When we know That, we shall not die with the body."}
{"label": 1, "text": "One who clings to the senses and to things that are ephemeral, must die many deaths, but that man who knows the eye of the eye, the ear of the ear, having severed himself from his physical nature, becomes immortal."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Immortality is attained when man transcends his apparent nature and finds that subtle, eternal and inexhaustible essence which is within him."}
{"label": 1, "text": "There the eye does not go, nor speech, nor mind."}
{"label": 1, "text": "We do not know That; we do not understand how It can be taught."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is distinct from the known and also It is beyond the unknown."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Thus we have heard from the ancient (teachers) who told us about It."}
{"label": 1, "text": "These physical eyes are unable to perceive that subtle essence."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Nor can it be expressed by finite language or known by finite intelligence, because it is infinite."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Our conception of knowing finite things is to know their name and form; but knowledge of God must be distinct from such knowledge."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This is why some declare God to be unknown and unknowable; because He is far more than eye or mind or speech can perceive, comprehend or express."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The Upanishad does not say that He cannot be known."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He is unknowable to man's finite nature."}
{"label": 1, "text": "How can a finite mortal apprehend the Infinite Whole?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "But He can be known by man's God-like nature."}
{"label": 1, "text": "That which speech does not illumine, but which illumines speech: know that alone to be the Brahman (the Supreme Being), not this which people worship here."}
{"label": 1, "text": "That which cannot be thought by mind, but by which, they say, mind is able to think: know that alone to be the Brahman, not this which people worship here."}
{"label": 1, "text": "That which is not seen by the eye, but by which the eye is able to see: know that alone to be the Brahman, not this which people worship here."}
{"label": 1, "text": "That which cannot be heard by the ear, but by which the ear is able to hear: know that alone to be Brahman, not this which people worship here."}
{"label": 1, "text": "If thou thinkest I know It well, then it is certain that thou knowest but little of the Brahman (Absolute Truth), or in what form He (resideth) in the Devas (minor aspects of Deity)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Therefore I think that what thou thinkest to be known is still to be sought after."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Having given the definition of the real Self or Brahman, by which mortals are able to see, hear, feel and think, the teacher was afraid that the disciple, after merely hearing about It, might conclude that he knew It."}
{"label": 1, "text": "So he said to him: You have heard about It, but that is not enough."}
{"label": 1, "text": "You must experience It."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Mere intellectual recognition will not give you true knowledge of It."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Neither can It be taught to you."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The teacher can only show the way."}
{"label": 1, "text": "You must find It for yourself."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Knowledge means union between subject and object."}
{"label": 1, "text": "To gain this union one must practice, theory cannot help us."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The previous chapter has shown that the knowledge of Brahman is beyond sense-perception: There the eye does not go, nor speech, nor mind."}
{"label": 1, "text": "That is distinct from known and also It is beyond the unknown."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Therefore it was necessary for the teacher to remind the disciple that knowledge based on sense-perception or intellectual apprehension should not be confounded with supersensuous knowledge."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Although the disciple had listened to the teacher with unquestioning mind and was intellectually convinced of the truth of his words, it was now necessary for him to prove by his own experience what he had heard."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Guided by the teacher, he sought within himself through meditation the meaning of Brahman; and having gained a new vision, he approached the teacher once more."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The disciple said: I do not think I know It well, nor do I think that I do not know It."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He among us who knows It truly, knows (what is meant by) I know and also what is meant by I know It not."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This appears to be contradictory, but it is not."}
{"label": 1, "text": "In the previous chapter we learned that Brahman is distinct from the known and beyond the unknown."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The disciple, realizing this, says: So far as mortal conception is concerned, I do not think I know, because I understand that It is beyond mind and speech; yet from the higher point of view, I cannot say that I do not know; for the very fact that I exist, that I can seek It, shows that I know; for It is the source of my being."}
{"label": 1, "text": "I do not know, however, in the sense of knowing the whole Infinite Ocean of existence."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The word knowledge is used ordinarily to signify acquaintance with phenomena only, but man must transcend this relative knowledge before he can have a clear conception of God."}
{"label": 1, "text": "One who wishes to attain Soul-consciousness must rise above matter."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The observation of material science being confined to the sense plane, it ignores what is beyond."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Therefore it must always be limited and subject to change."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It discovered atoms, then it went further and discovered electrons, and when it had found the one, it had to drop the other; so this kind of knowledge can never lead to the ultimate knowledge of the Infinite, because it is exclusive and not inclusive."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Spiritual science is not merely a question of mind and brain, it depends on the awakening of our latent higher consciousness."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who thinks he knows It not, knows It."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who thinks he knows It, knows It not."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The true knowers think they can never know It (because of Its infinitude), while the ignorant think they know It."}
{"label": 1, "text": "By this text the teacher confirms the idea that Brahman is unthinkable, because unconditioned."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Therefore he says: He who considers It beyond thought, beyond sense-perception, beyond mind and speech, he alone has a true understanding of Brahman."}
{"label": 1, "text": "They who judge a living being from his external form and sense faculties, know him not; because the real Self of man is not manifested in his seeing, hearing, speaking."}
{"label": 1, "text": "His real Self is that within by which he hears and speaks and sees."}
{"label": 1, "text": "In the same way he knows not Brahman who thinks he knows It by name and form."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The arrogant and foolish man thinks he knows everything; but the true knower is humble."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He says: How can I know Thee, who art Infinite and beyond mind and speech?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "In the last portion of the text, the teacher draws an impressive contrast between the attitude of the wise man who knows, but thinks he does not know; and that of the ignorant who does not know, but thinks he knows."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It (Brahman) is known, when It is known in every state of consciousness."}
{"label": 1, "text": "(Through such knowledge) one attains immortality."}
{"label": 1, "text": "By attaining this Self, man gains strength; and by Self-knowledge immortality is attained."}
{"label": 1, "text": "We have learned from the previous text that the Brahman is unknown to those whose knowledge is limited to sense experience; but He is not unknown to those whose purified intelligence perceives Him as the basis of all states of consciousness and the essence of all things."}
{"label": 1, "text": "By this higher knowledge a man attains immortality, because he knows that although his body may decay and die, the subtle essence of his being remains untouched."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Such an one also acquires unlimited strength, because he identifies himself with the ultimate Source."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The strength which comes from one's own muscle and brain or from one's individual power must be limited and mortal and therefore cannot lift one beyond death; but through the strength which Atma-gnana or Self-knowledge gives, immortality is reached."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Whenever knowledge is based on direct perception of this undying essence, one transcends all fear of death and becomes immortal."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The Brahman once won a victory for the Devas."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Through that victory of the Brahman, the Devas became elated."}
{"label": 1, "text": "They thought, This victory is ours."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This glory is ours."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Brahman here does not mean a personal Deity."}
{"label": 1, "text": "There is a Brahma, the first person of the Hindu Trinity; but Brahman is the Absolute, the One without a second, the essence of all."}
{"label": 1, "text": "There are different names and forms which represent certain personal aspects of Divinity, such as Brahma the Creator, Vishnu the Preserver and Siva the Transformer; but no one of these can fully represent the Whole."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Brahman is the vast ocean of being, on which rise numberless ripples and waves of manifestation."}
{"label": 1, "text": "From the smallest atomic form to a Deva or an angel, all spring from that limitless ocean of Brahman, the inexhaustible Source of life."}
{"label": 1, "text": "No manifested form of life can be independent of its source, just as no wave, however mighty, can be independent of the ocean."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Nothing moves without that Power."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He is the only Doer."}
{"label": 1, "text": "But the Devas thought: This victory is ours, this glory is ours."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The Brahman perceived this and appeared before them."}
{"label": 1, "text": "They did not know what mysterious form it was."}
{"label": 1, "text": "They said to Fire: O Jataveda (All-knowing)!"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Find out what mysterious spirit this is."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He said: Yes."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He ran towards it and He (Brahman) said to him: Who art thou?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "I am Agni, I am Jataveda, he (the Fire-god) replied."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Brahman asked: What power resides in thee?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Agni replied: I can burn up all whatsoever exists on earth."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Brahman placed a straw before him and said: Burn this."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He (Agni) rushed towards it with all speed, but was not able to burn it."}
{"label": 1, "text": "So he returned from there and said (to the Devas): I was not able to find out what this great mystery is."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Then they said to Vayu (the Air-god): Vayu!"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Find out what this mystery is."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He said: Yes."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He ran towards it and He (Brahman) said to him: Who art thou?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "I am Vayu, I am Matarisva (traveller of Heaven), he (Vayu) said."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Then the Brahman said: What power is in thee?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Vayu replied: I can blow away all whatsoever exists on earth."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Brahman placed a straw before him and said: Blow this away."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He (Vayu) rushed towards it with all speed, but was not able to blow it away."}
{"label": 1, "text": "So he returned from there and said (to the Devas): I was not able to find out what this great mystery is."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Then they said to Indra: O Maghavan (Worshipful One)!"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Find out what this mystery is."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He said: Yes; and ran towards it, but it disappeared before him."}
{"label": 1, "text": "She (Uma) said: It is Brahman."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is through the victory of Brahman that ye are victorious."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Then from her words, he (Indra) knew that it (that mysterious form) was Brahman."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Uma replied to Indra, It is to Brahman that you owe your victory."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is through His power that you live and act."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He is the agent and you are all only instruments in His hands."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Therefore your idea that 'This victory is ours, this glory is ours,' is based on ignorance."}
{"label": 1, "text": "At once Indra saw their mistake."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The Devas, being puffed up with vanity, had thought they themselves had achieved the victory, whereas it was Brahman; for not even a blade of grass can move without His command."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Therefore these Devas,--Agni, Vayu and Indra--excel other Devas, because they came nearer to Brahman."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It was they who first knew this spirit as Brahman."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Therefore Indra excels all other Devas, because he came nearest to Brahman, and because he first (before all others) knew this spirit as Brahman."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Agni, Vayu and Indra were superior to the other Devas because they gained a closer vision; and they were able to do this because they were purer; while Indra stands as the head of the Devas, because he realized the Truth directly, he reached Brahman."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The significance of this is that whoever comes in direct touch with Brahman or the Supreme is glorified."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Thus the teaching of Brahman is here illustrated in regard to the Devas."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He dashed like lightning, and appeared and disappeared just as the eye winks."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The teaching as regards the Devas was that Brahman is the only Doer."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He had appeared before them in a mysterious form; but the whole of the unfathomable Brahman could not be seen in any definite form; so at the moment of vanishing, He manifested more of His immeasurable glory and fleetness of action by a sudden dazzling flash of light."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Next (the teaching) is regarding Adhyatman (the embodied Soul)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The mind seems to approach Him (Brahman)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "By this mind (the seeker) again and again remembers and thinks about Brahman."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Only by the mind can the seeker after knowledge approach Brahman, whose nature in glory and speed has been described as like unto a flash of lightning."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Mind alone can picture the indescribable Brahman; and mind alone, being swift in its nature, can follow Him."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is through the help of this mind that we can think and meditate on Brahman; and when by constant thought of Him the mind becomes purified, then like a polished mirror it can reflect His Divine Glory."}
{"label": 1, "text": "That Brahman is called Tadvanam (object of adoration)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He is to be worshipped by the name Tadvanam."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who knows Brahman thus, is loved by all beings."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Brahman is the object of adoration and the goal of all beings."}
{"label": 1, "text": "For this reason he should be worshipped and meditated upon as Tadvanam."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Whoever knows Him in this aspect becomes one with Him, and serves as a clear channel through which the blessings of Brahman flow out to others."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The knower of God partakes of all His lovable qualities and is therefore loved by all true devotees."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The disciple asked: O Master, teach me the Upanishad."}
{"label": 1, "text": "(The teacher replied:) The Upanishad has been taught thee."}
{"label": 1, "text": "We have certainly taught thee the Upanishad about Brahman."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The Upanishad is based on tapas (practice of the control of body, mind and senses), dama (subjugation of the senses), karma (right performance of prescribed actions)."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The Vedas are its limbs."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Truth is its support."}
{"label": 1, "text": "He who knows this (wisdom of the Upanishad), having been cleansed of all sin, becomes established in the blissful, eternal and highest abode of Brahman, in the highest abode of Brahman."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Union, here as always in the Scriptures of India, means union of the individual soul with the Oversoul; of the personal consciousness with the Divine Consciousness, whereby the mortal becomes immortal, and enters the Eternal."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Therefore, salvation is, first, freedom from sin and the sorrow which comes from sin, and then a divine and eternal well-being, wherein the soul partakes of the being, the wisdom and glory of God."}
{"label": 1, "text": "versatile psychic nature."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The goal is the full consciousness of the spiritual man, illumined by the Divine Light."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Nothing except the obdurate resistance of the psychic nature keeps us back from the goal."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The psychical powers are spiritual powers run wild, perverted, drawn from their proper channel."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Therefore our first task is, to regain control of this perverted nature, to chasten, purify and restore the misplaced powers."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Egotism is but the perversion of spiritual being."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Ambition is the inversion of spiritual power."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Passion is the distortion of love."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The mortal is the limitation of the immortal."}
{"label": 1, "text": "When these false images give place to true, then the spiritual man stands forth luminous, as the sun, when the clouds disperse."}
{"label": 1, "text": "psychic nature."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The power and life which are the heritage of the spiritual man have been caught and enmeshed in psychical activities."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Instead of pure being in the Divine, there has been fretful, combative, egotism, its hand against every man."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Instead of the light of pure vision, there have been restless senses nave been re and imaginings."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Instead of spiritual joy, the undivided joy of pure being, there has been self-indulgence of body and mind."}
{"label": 1, "text": "These are all real forces, but distorted from their true nature and goal."}
{"label": 1, "text": "They must be extricated, like gems from the matrix, like the pith from the reed, steadily, without destructive violence."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Spiritual powers are to be drawn forth from the psychic meshes."}
{"label": 1, "text": "to the five hindrances (Book II, )."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The psychic nature is built up through the image-making power, the power which lies behind and dwells in mind-pictures."}
{"label": 1, "text": "These pictures do not remain quiescent in the mind; they are kinetic, restless, stimulating to new acts."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Thus the mind-image of an indulgence suggests and invites to a new indulgence; the picture of past joy is framed in regrets or hopes."}
{"label": 1, "text": "And there is the ceaseless play of the desire to know, to penetrate to the essence of things, to classify."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This, too, busies itself ceaselessly with the mind-images."}
{"label": 1, "text": "So that we may classify the activities of the psychic nature thus:"}
{"label": 1, "text": "predication, sleep, memory."}
{"label": 1, "text": "We have here a list of mental and emotional powers; of powers that picture and observe, and of powers that picture and feel."}
{"label": 1, "text": "But the power to know and feel is spiritual and immortal."}
{"label": 1, "text": "What is needed is, not to destroy it, but to raise it from the psychical to the spiritual realm."}
{"label": 1, "text": "reason, and trustworthy testimony."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Each of these is a spiritual power, thinly veiled."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Direct observation is the outermost form of the Soul's pure vision."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Inductive reason rests on the great principles of continuity and correspondence; and these, on the supreme truth that all life is of the One."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Trustworthy testimony, the sharing of one soul in the wisdom of another, rests on the ultimate oneness of all souls."}
{"label": 1, "text": "perception of the true nature of things."}
{"label": 1, "text": "When the object is not truly perceived, when the observation is inaccurate and faulty, thought or reasoning based on that mistaken perception is of necessity false and unsound."}
{"label": 1, "text": "an object perceived."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The purpose of this Sutra is, to distinguish between the mental process of predication, and observation, induction or testimony."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Predication is the attribution of a quality or action to a subject, by adding to it a predicate."}
{"label": 1, "text": "In the sentence, the man is wise, the man is the subject; is wise is the predicate."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This may be simply an interplay of thoughts, without the presence of the object thought of; or the things thought of may be imaginary or unreal; while observation, induction and testimony always go back to an object."}
{"label": 1, "text": "material things being absent."}
{"label": 1, "text": "In waking life, we have two currents of perception; an outer current of physical things seen and heard and perceived; an inner current of mind-images and thoughts."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The outer current ceases in sleep; the inner current continues, and watching the mind-images float before the field of consciousness, we dream."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Even when there are no dreams, there is still a certain consciousness in sleep, so that, on waking, one says, I have slept well, or I have slept badly."}
{"label": 1, "text": "modifying them."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Here, as before, the mental power is explained in terms of mind-images, which are the material of which the psychic world is built, Therefore the sages teach that the world of our perception, which is indeed a world of mind-images, is but the wraith or shadow of the real and everlasting world."}
{"label": 1, "text": "In this sense, memory is but the psychical inversion of the spiritual, ever-present vision."}
{"label": 1, "text": "That which is ever before the spiritual eye of the Seer needs not to be remembered."}
{"label": 1, "text": "of the will, and through ceasing from self-indulgence."}
{"label": 1, "text": "If these psychical powers and energies, even such evil things as passion and hate and fear, are but spiritual powers fallen and perverted, how are we to bring about their release and restoration?"}
{"label": 1, "text": "Two means are presented to us: the awakening of the spiritual will, and the purification of mind and thought."}
{"label": 1, "text": "being."}
{"label": 1, "text": "We have thought of ourselves, perhaps, as creatures moving upon this earth, rather helpless, at the mercy of storm and hunger and our enemies."}
{"label": 1, "text": "We are to think of ourselves as immortals, dwelling in the Light, encompassed and sustained by spiritual powers."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The steady effort to hold this thought will awaken dormant and unrealized powers, which will unveil to us the nearness of the Eternal."}
{"label": 1, "text": "persistently, with earnestness."}
{"label": 1, "text": "We must seek spiritual life in conformity with the laws of spiritual life, with earnestness, humility, gentle charity, which is an acknowledgment of the One Soul within us all."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Only through obedience to that shared Life, through perpetual remembrance of our oneness with all Divine Being, our nothingness apart from Divine Being, can we enter our inheritance."}
{"label": 1, "text": "for sensuous pleasure here or hereafter."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Rightly understood, the desire for sensation is the desire of being, the distortion of the soul's eternal life."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The lust of sensual stimulus and excitation rests on the longing to feel one's life keenly, to gain the sense of being really alive."}
