{"label": 1, "text": "The reason is this: The threefold power we have been considering, the triad of Attention, Contemplation, Meditation is, so far as we have yet considered it, the focussing of the beam of perceiving consciousness upon some form of manifesting being, with a view of understanding it completely."}
{"label": 1, "text": "There is a higher stage, where the beam of consciousness is turned back upon itself, and the individual consciousness enters into, and knows, the All consciousness."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This is a being, a being in immortality, rather than a knowing; it is free from mental analysis or mental forms."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is not an activity of the higher mind, even the mind of the spiritual man."}
{"label": 1, "text": "It is an activity of the soul."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Had Newton risen to this higher stage, he would have known, not the laws of motion, but that high Being, from whose Life comes eternal motion."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Had Darwin risen to this, he would have seen the Soul, whose graduated thought and being all evolution expresses."}
{"label": 1, "text": "There are, therefore, these two perceptions: that of living things, and that of the Life; that of the Soul's works, and that of the Soul itself."}
{"label": 1, "text": "there is the overcoming of the mind-impress of excitation."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Then comes the manifestation of the mind-impress of Control."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Then the perceiving consciousness follows after the moment of Control."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This is the development of Control."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The meaning seems to be this: Some object enters the field of observation, and at first violently excites the mind, stirring up curiosity, fear, wonder; then the consciousness returns upon itself, as it were, and takes the perception firmly in hand, steadying itself, and viewing the matter calmly from above."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This steadying effort of the will upon the perceiving consciousness is Control, and immediately upon it follows perception, understanding, insight."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Take a trite example."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Supposing one is walking in an Indian forest."}
{"label": 1, "text": "A charging elephant suddenly appears."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The man is excited by astonishment, and, perhaps, terror."}
{"label": 1, "text": "But he exercises an effort of will, perceives the situation in its true bearings, and recognizes that a certain thing must be done; in this case, probably, that he must get out of the way as quickly as possible."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Or a comet, unheralded, appears in the sky like a flaming sword."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The beholder is at first astonished, perhaps terror-stricken; but he takes himself in hand, controls his thoughts, views the apparition calmly, and finally calculates its orbit and its relation to meteor showers."}
{"label": 1, "text": "These are extreme illustrations; but with all knowledge the order of perception is the same: first, the excitation of the mind by the new object impressed on it; then the control of the mind from within; upon which follows the perception of the nature of the object."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Where the eyes of the spiritual man are open, this will be a true and penetrating spiritual perception."}
{"label": 1, "text": "In some such way do our living experiences come to us; first, with a shock of pain; then the Soul steadies itself and controls the pain; then the spirit perceives the lesson of the event, and its bearing upon the progressive revelation of life."}
{"label": 1, "text": "habituated to it, and there arises an equable flow of perceiving consciousness."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Control of the mind by the Soul, like control of the muscles by the mind, comes by practice, and constant voluntary repetition."}
{"label": 1, "text": "As an example of control of the muscles by the mind, take the ceaseless practice by which a musician gains mastery over his instrument, or a fencer gains skill with a rapier."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Innumerable small efforts of attention will make a result which seems well-nigh miraculous; which, for the novice, is really miraculous."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Then consider that far more wonderful instrument, the perceiving mind, played on by that fine musician, the Soul."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Here again, innumerable small efforts of attention will accumulate into mastery, and a mastery worth winning."}
{"label": 1, "text": "For a concrete example, take the gradual conquest of each day, the effort to live that day for the Soul."}
