{"label": 1, "text": "Here we come to a high and difficult matter, which has always been held to be of great moment in the Eastern wisdom: the thought that the division of time into past, present and future is, in great measure, an illusion; that past, present, future all dwell together in the eternal Now."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The discernment of this truth has been held to be so necessarily a part of wisdom, that one of the names of the Enlightened is: he who has passed beyond the three times: past, present, future."}
{"label": 1, "text": "So the Western Master said: Before Abraham was, I am; and again, I am with you always, unto the end of the world; using the eternal present for past and future alike."}
{"label": 1, "text": "With the same purpose, the Master speaks of himself as the alpha and the omega, the beginning and the end, the first and the last."}
{"label": 1, "text": "And a Master of our own days writes: I feel even irritated at having to use these three clumsy words--past, present, and future."}
