{"label": 1, "text": "To the psychic nature belong all the ebb and flow of emotion, all hoping and fearing, desire and hate: the things that make the multitude of men and women deem themselves happy or miserable."}
{"label": 1, "text": "To it also belong the measuring and comparing, the doubt and questioning, which, for the same multitude, make up mental life."}
{"label": 1, "text": "So that there results the emotion-soaked personality, with its dark and narrow view of life: the shivering, terror driven personality that is life itself for all but all of mankind."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Yet the personality is not the true man, not the living soul at all, but only a spectacle which the true man observes."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Let us under stand this, therefore, and draw ourselves up inwardly to the height of the Spiritual Man, who, standing in the quiet light of the Eternal, looks down serene upon this turmoil of the outer life."}
{"label": 1, "text": "One first masters the personality, the mind, by thus looking down on it from above, from within; by steadily watching its ebb and flow, as objective, outward, and therefore not the real Self."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This standing back is the first step, detachment."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The second, to maintain the vantage-ground thus gained, is recollection."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This is a further step toward overthrowing the tyranny of the mind: the psychic nature of emotion and mental measuring."}
{"label": 1, "text": "This psychic self, the personality, claims to be absolute, asserting that life is for it and through it; it seeks to impose on the whole being of man its narrow, materialistic, faithless view of life and the universe; it would clip the wings of the soaring Soul."}
{"label": 1, "text": "But the Soul dethrones the tyrant, by perceiving and steadily affirming that the psychic self is no true self at all, not self-luminous, but only an object of observation, watched by the serene eyes of the Spiritual Man."}
{"label": 1, "text": "external to it."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The truth is that the mind knows neither external things nor itself."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Its measuring and analyzing, its hoping and fearing, hating and desiring, never give it a true measure of life, nor any sense of real values."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Ceaselessly active, it never really attains to knowledge; or, if we admit its knowledge, it ever falls short of wisdom, which comes only through intuition, the vision of the Spiritual Man."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Life cannot be known by the mind, its secrets cannot be learned through the mind."}
{"label": 1, "text": "The proof is, the ceaseless strife and contradiction of opinion among those who trust in the mind."}
{"label": 1, "text": "Much less can the mind know itself, the more so, because it is pervaded by the illusion that it truly knows, truly is."}
{"label": 1, "text": "True knowledge of the mind comes, first, when the Spiritual Man, arising, stands detached, regarding the mind from above, with quiet eyes, and seeing it for the tangled web of psychic forces that it truly is."}
{"label": 1, "text": "But the truth is divined long before it is clearly seen, and then begins the long battle of the mind, against the Real, the mind fighting doggedly, craftily, for its supremacy."}
